maintaining the status quo,

00:11:47.250 --> 00:11:49.680
they essentially
push the knife deeper

00:11:49.680 --> 00:11:52.500
into the back of the
African-American community.

00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:54.270
So until such time
as individuals

00:11:54.270 --> 00:11:56.970
decide that they wish
to disrupt the system,

00:11:56.970 --> 00:11:59.060
they have to accept
or allow themselves

00:11:59.060 --> 00:12:02.170
to be lulled into sleep
that the system isn't bad,

00:12:02.170 --> 00:12:05.000
and that we actually
want it this way.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.350
So when we start
saying, actually, I

00:12:07.350 --> 00:12:09.000
don't want to this way.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.369
I'd like it kind of
like you have it,

00:12:11.369 --> 00:12:13.660
where you don't worry about
police officers pulling you

00:12:13.660 --> 00:12:15.425
over, or you don't
have to worry,

00:12:15.425 --> 00:12:17.800
as I did when my children
played in our own neighborhood,

00:12:17.800 --> 00:12:20.730
that one of my own
neighbors was going

00:12:20.730 --> 00:12:22.570
to say that they
were carrying a gun

00:12:22.570 --> 00:12:26.440
and that four squad cars would
come after my 11-year-old

00:12:26.440 --> 00:12:29.030
on the night of
his 11th birthday.

00:12:29.030 --> 00:12:31.180
I'd like it like
you have it, where

00:12:31.180 --> 00:12:35.600
you can have your kids play in
your neighborhood without fear.

00:12:35.600 --> 00:12:40.580
When some white
people begin to awaken

00:12:40.580 --> 00:12:43.780
to the depth of the
reality of the pain

00:12:43.780 --> 00:12:45.167
that it is to be
African-American

00:12:45.167 --> 00:12:46.750
in this country,
they're going to have

00:12:46.750 --> 00:12:48.412
to do something about it.

00:12:48.412 --> 00:12:50.370
They're going to have to
do something about it.

00:12:50.370 --> 00:12:51.210
ROLAND MARTIN: Carmen.

00:12:51.210 --> 00:12:52.751
CARMEN PEREZ: And
so I want everybody

00:12:52.751 --> 00:12:55.660
to put your hands out.

00:12:55.660 --> 00:12:57.860
Put them together.

00:12:57.860 --> 00:13:00.210
Right, that's easy.

00:13:00.210 --> 00:13:01.720
Now try doing it
the opposite way.

00:13:05.680 --> 00:13:09.720
Try doing it to where
it's uncomfortable.

00:13:09.720 --> 00:13:11.780
And I always tell
people, if you are

00:13:11.780 --> 00:13:16.360
comfortable with seeing black
and brown people oppressed,

00:13:16.360 --> 00:13:19.410
you are part of the problem.

00:13:19.410 --> 00:13:21.730
And I don't know
anybody's story here.

00:13:21.730 --> 00:13:23.890
And I'm not going to say,
oh, I can relate to you,

00:13:23.890 --> 00:13:26.710
and we've been down
this path or whatever.

00:13:26.710 --> 00:13:29.990
But I do know that
when something

00:13:29.990 --> 00:13:32.920
impacts your community,
you want to change it.

00:13:35.580 --> 00:13:38.280
And so we're all up here
because there's something

00:13:38.280 --> 00:13:40.570
that happened in our lives.

00:13:40.570 --> 00:13:42.560
I'm making assumptions
now up here,

00:13:42.560 --> 00:13:45.530
but there's something that
happened in our lives that

00:13:45.530 --> 00:13:48.580
told us no more.

00:13:48.580 --> 00:13:50.590
Enough is enough.

00:13:50.590 --> 00:13:54.970
Whether you grew up in a
community that was plagued

00:13:54.970 --> 00:13:58.530
by violence, whether you
witnessed your brother hog

00:13:58.530 --> 00:14:02.560
tied, whether you had a sister
[INAUDIBLE]-- whatever it was,

00:14:02.560 --> 00:14:05.820
there was something that
then changed the trajectory

00:14:05.820 --> 00:14:11.050
of your life to
be a change agent.

00:14:11.050 --> 00:14:17.330
And so it's the fact that
when I walk down the street,

00:14:17.330 --> 00:14:20.000
I could see somebody
being handcuffed,

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.360
and that person looks like me.

00:14:22.360 --> 00:14:25.010
It's the fact that when
I walk into a prison,

00:14:25.010 --> 00:14:28.380
and I walk into a detention
center, the young women

00:14:28.380 --> 00:14:31.880
that I'm serving look like me.

00:14:31.880 --> 00:14:36.650
It's the fact that I
could walk into Google,

00:14:36.650 --> 00:14:41.360
and I don't really see
anybody that looks like me. .

00:14:41.360 --> 00:14:46.320
So it's a larger question
about you digging deeper, going

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:52.880
into the cavern of your heart,
and asking, what can I do?

00:14:52.880 --> 00:14:56.980
Because it shouldn't be
about you feeling my pain.

00:14:56.980 --> 00:15:00.090
It should be about the fact
that we all, like you said,

00:15:00.090 --> 00:15:03.040
brother, want to be able
to walk down the street.

00:15:03.040 --> 00:15:06.720
I want to be able to
walk downtown Chicago

00:15:06.720 --> 00:15:09.560
and not feel like I'm in a
community that is gentrified,

00:15:09.560 --> 00:15:11.780
because the only people
that I was walking down

00:15:11.780 --> 00:15:15.900
the street that looked like me
were the servers or the host.

00:15:15.900 --> 00:15:19.710
I want to be able to have
children and tell them

00:15:19.710 --> 00:15:23.470
they could be anything--
anything in the world.

00:15:23.470 --> 00:15:25.500
I want to be able to have
the type of lifestyle

00:15:25.500 --> 00:15:29.110
that I've seen around
other colleagues, right?

00:15:29.110 --> 00:15:30.450
That's all I want.

00:15:30.450 --> 00:15:33.550
And so I work hard
every single day.

00:15:33.550 --> 00:15:36.040
And I'm involved in the
Black Lives Matter movement,

00:15:36.040 --> 00:15:37.340
and people are like,
well, you're Latina.

00:15:37.340 --> 00:15:38.020
Why do you care?

00:15:38.020 --> 00:15:40.640
And I'm like, because
I had black teachers.

00:15:40.640 --> 00:15:43.730
I had black coaches.

00:15:43.730 --> 00:15:44.810
And I had black pastors.

00:15:48.070 --> 00:15:49.080
I've traveled the world.

00:15:49.080 --> 00:15:49.840
I've been to Cuba.

00:15:49.840 --> 00:15:51.090
I've been to all these places.

00:15:51.090 --> 00:15:52.980
And I've seen that
black people are

00:15:52.980 --> 00:15:56.320
oppressed all over the world.

00:15:56.320 --> 00:16:00.250
You don't need to come to a
race conversation to see that.

00:16:00.250 --> 00:16:04.280
You see it every single day
when you turn on turn on CNN,

00:16:04.280 --> 00:16:06.840
or you turn on Fox,
whatever people prefer.

00:16:06.840 --> 00:16:10.610
You see it every
single day, right?

00:16:10.610 --> 00:16:14.030
And so I know that once
black people are free,

00:16:14.030 --> 00:16:15.112
my people are free.

00:16:15.112 --> 00:16:17.070
ROLAND MARTIN: The thing
I think is interesting

00:16:17.070 --> 00:16:21.050
when you talk about seeing--
I've lived and worked

00:16:21.050 --> 00:16:23.420
in Chicago for six years.

00:16:23.420 --> 00:16:26.540
And what many of you here
in this room, whether you're

00:16:26.540 --> 00:16:28.180
black, white, Hispanic--
doesn't matter

00:16:28.180 --> 00:16:32.290
who you are-- you may not
realize that in this city, when

00:16:32.290 --> 00:16:34.910
they have the tourist
maps of Chicago,

00:16:34.910 --> 00:16:36.910
it did not extend
past 22nd Street.

00:16:36.910 --> 00:16:39.590
DAVID STOVAL: Trust.

00:16:39.590 --> 00:16:43.280
ROLAND MARTIN: It didn't
go into Bronzeville.

00:16:43.280 --> 00:16:46.130
It did not literally
go past 22nd Street.

00:16:46.130 --> 00:16:50.970
So what that said in Chicago--
if you come to Chicago,

00:16:50.970 --> 00:16:57.330
we only want you to
go from here to here.

00:16:57.330 --> 00:17:00.140
And it's amazing
how a lot of people,

00:17:00.140 --> 00:17:02.580
again, don't have the
context to understand

00:17:02.580 --> 00:17:04.119
a city like this
here-- Jeff, I want

00:17:04.119 --> 00:17:08.160
you to speak to this-- also
have and understand the history.

00:17:08.160 --> 00:17:10.770
And I want to use
Chicago as the example.

00:17:10.770 --> 00:17:14.829
Harold Washington runs
for mayor in 1983,

00:17:14.829 --> 00:17:19.240
and the racial
hatred that existed

00:17:19.240 --> 00:17:22.800
that a sitting member of
Congress who was black

00:17:22.800 --> 00:17:26.859
would dare run to
be mayor of a city

00:17:26.859 --> 00:17:29.630
with the second-largest
concentration

00:17:29.630 --> 00:17:33.460
of black people outside
the continent of Africa.

00:17:33.460 --> 00:17:35.510
JEFF JOHNSON: So
what's the question?

00:17:35.510 --> 00:17:36.926
ROLAND MARTIN:
Question is, I want

00:17:36.926 --> 00:17:40.700
you to speak to that
experience and how

00:17:40.700 --> 00:17:43.320
folks who might live
here present day

00:17:43.320 --> 00:17:46.190
doesn't realize that,
oh yeah, that was 1983,

00:17:46.190 --> 00:17:49.950
but it still lives and permeates
the city and its structure

00:17:49.950 --> 00:17:51.140
today.

00:17:51.140 --> 00:17:55.290
JEFF JOHNSON: Well, I think
one, any time marginalized

00:17:55.290 --> 00:17:59.610
people have the gumption
to lead not just those that

00:17:59.610 --> 00:18:03.214
are marginalized,
but everybody, there

00:18:03.214 --> 00:18:04.380
are two things that happens.

00:18:04.380 --> 00:18:07.790
Number one, it
says, oh my god, we

00:18:07.790 --> 00:18:09.800
don't want them in control
of the purse strings.

00:18:12.540 --> 00:18:16.010
And let's be honest,
because I think

00:18:16.010 --> 00:18:18.330
when we have this race
conversation, a lot Of times we

00:18:18.330 --> 00:18:21.620
have it through the lens of we
as marginalized people are only

00:18:21.620 --> 00:18:23.280
talking to white people.

00:18:23.280 --> 00:18:25.049
There's multi-level
conversations

00:18:25.049 --> 00:18:26.340
that need to be happening here.

00:18:26.340 --> 00:18:28.230
And so even we have
these conversations

00:18:28.230 --> 00:18:30.990
about black political
power, black political power

00:18:30.990 --> 00:18:33.780
has never been about
black political positions.

00:18:33.780 --> 00:18:37.850
And so when you think about what
happened in Chicago, similar

00:18:37.850 --> 00:18:40.830
to what happened in Atlanta,
similar to what happened in DC,

00:18:40.830 --> 00:18:44.590
these mayors were powerful, not
just because they were black

00:18:44.590 --> 00:18:47.870
and they were able to
get control of City Hall.

00:18:47.870 --> 00:18:50.700
They were powerful because
they shifted the very resources

00:18:50.700 --> 00:18:53.270
of the city to create
black millionaires,

00:18:53.270 --> 00:18:55.500
to create opportunity,
to create power.

00:18:55.500 --> 00:18:58.170
And while they didn't give it
to everybody-- let's be clear.

00:18:58.170 --> 00:19:01.150
Everybody didn't get it--
there was a shift of power

00:19:01.150 --> 00:19:02.590
that scared people.

00:19:02.590 --> 00:19:05.770
And so whether it was
Maynard Jackson in Atlanta,

00:19:05.770 --> 00:19:09.640
or whether it was Marion
Barry in Washington DC,

00:19:09.640 --> 00:19:12.970
or whether it was the first
black mayor in Cleveland, Ohio,

00:19:12.970 --> 00:19:17.050
with Carl Stokes,
the fear was not just

00:19:17.050 --> 00:19:21.250
about the gumption of thinking
that you could have power.

00:19:21.250 --> 00:19:25.340
It was what ultimately happens
when this individual has

00:19:25.340 --> 00:19:29.400
the ability to shift wealth
and to shift resources

00:19:29.400 --> 00:19:31.670
and to shift what
communities look like?

00:19:31.670 --> 00:19:34.980
And to Carmen's point,
the real challenge

00:19:34.980 --> 00:19:37.890
is because so many
of these cities

00:19:37.890 --> 00:19:42.220
have been designed with
disenfranchisement in mind,

00:19:42.220 --> 00:19:45.390
folks that were never a part
of those other communities

00:19:45.390 --> 00:19:48.280
have never been able to
see the inherent value

00:19:48.280 --> 00:19:50.710
in broad-based
economic development.

00:19:50.710 --> 00:19:52.500
So I live in a
city like Baltimore

00:19:52.500 --> 00:19:58.370
that I think has had decades of
intentional lack of development

00:19:58.370 --> 00:19:59.930
in certain parts of
the city that are

00:19:59.930 --> 00:20:02.460
primarily black and poor white.

00:20:02.460 --> 00:20:05.720
And Baltimore has billions
of dollars in development.

00:20:05.720 --> 00:20:07.030
The harbor looks fantastic.

00:20:07.030 --> 00:20:10.069
The communities that extend
from the harbor look amazing.

00:20:10.069 --> 00:20:11.860
People come to Baltimore,
and they love it.

00:20:11.860 --> 00:20:13.010
They get to go
down to the water.

00:20:13.010 --> 00:20:14.040
They get to get some crabs.

00:20:14.040 --> 00:20:15.415
They have a great
time at hotels.

00:20:15.415 --> 00:20:16.090
They shop.

00:20:16.090 --> 00:20:19.320
But you have block upon
block upon block upon block

00:20:19.320 --> 00:20:22.750
upon block of some of the
worst blight in America,

00:20:22.750 --> 00:20:25.840
and not under 1 mayor,
or 2 mayors, or 3 mayors,

00:20:25.840 --> 00:20:28.230
or 4 mayors-- of 10 mayors.

00:20:28.230 --> 00:20:30.270
That doesn't happen by accident.

00:20:30.270 --> 00:20:35.040
And so the challenge is
for those people of color

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:37.160
or marginalized people
that get into power--

00:20:37.160 --> 00:20:42.760
the disruption is not
you being elected.

00:20:42.760 --> 00:20:45.260
The disruption is, do you
do something different

00:20:45.260 --> 00:20:47.680
when you are there
to shift power

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:50.940
in a way that creates
disruption versus you giving

00:20:50.940 --> 00:20:53.260
the appearance of
disruption by you being

00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:55.650
the first, second, or third
person of color that's

00:20:55.650 --> 00:20:56.510
in this position?

00:20:56.510 --> 00:20:57.770
ROLAND MARTIN: And that's
what I wanted to go to Jeff,

00:20:57.770 --> 00:20:59.280
because I want--
and anyone can jump

00:20:59.280 --> 00:21:03.000
in on this one, because when
we talk about revolution

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:07.430
and disruption, what we are
facing right now in 2016,

00:21:07.430 --> 00:21:12.000
this is a battle over power.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:15.920
And this is a generation
that has seen--

00:21:15.920 --> 00:21:18.090
that's post-civil rights.

00:21:18.090 --> 00:21:20.300
They saw integration.

00:21:20.300 --> 00:21:23.860
They saw Dr. King,
Fanny Lou Hamer.

00:21:23.860 --> 00:21:25.660
They saw so many others.

00:21:25.660 --> 00:21:28.210
And they said, no.

00:21:28.210 --> 00:21:30.000
We don't want equality.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:31.380
We want power.

00:21:31.380 --> 00:21:33.090
CARMEN PEREZ: And just
to kind of go back

00:21:33.090 --> 00:21:35.390
to what you were saying
in regards to SNCC,

00:21:35.390 --> 00:21:37.000
they organized.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:40.830
They were able to accomplish
so many victories.

00:21:40.830 --> 00:21:42.380
But when you look
at the victory,

00:21:42.380 --> 00:21:46.090
right, gaining the
opportunity to integrate,

00:21:46.090 --> 00:21:48.310
you were integrating
what Mr Belafonte

00:21:48.310 --> 00:21:52.100
talks about-- his last
conversation with Dr. King was.

00:21:52.100 --> 00:21:54.610
They were integrating
into a burning house.

00:21:54.610 --> 00:21:57.220
So Dr. King then says, so
then, what do we become?

00:21:57.220 --> 00:21:58.405
And he says, fireman.

00:21:58.405 --> 00:21:59.780
But at the end of
the day you're,

00:21:59.780 --> 00:22:03.050
integrating institutions
that were racist.

00:22:03.050 --> 00:22:05.010
So nobody woke up the
next day and said,

00:22:05.010 --> 00:22:09.590
hey, we're walking being black
children into our schools.

00:22:09.590 --> 00:22:12.790
Look at how what happened
with the Little Rock Nine.

00:22:12.790 --> 00:22:15.370
And so for me, I always
ask Mr Belafonte,

00:22:15.370 --> 00:22:17.940
what was the integration plan?

00:22:17.940 --> 00:22:20.470
So you made the
assumption that there

00:22:20.470 --> 00:22:26.410
was no more racism in
America after that went away.

00:22:26.410 --> 00:22:29.140
However, there was no
real integration plan.

00:22:29.140 --> 00:22:30.860
And these institutions
are still racist.

00:22:30.860 --> 00:22:32.050
JEFF JOHNSON: But that
was never the plan.

00:22:32.050 --> 00:22:33.130
CARMEN PEREZ: Right.

00:22:33.130 --> 00:22:33.820
JEFF JOHNSON: But
I think there's

00:22:33.820 --> 00:22:36.480
a misnomer when we talk about
civil rights and social justice

00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:37.450
of the 60s.

00:22:37.450 --> 00:22:38.880
The plan was never integration.

00:22:38.880 --> 00:22:40.400
It was desegregation.

00:22:40.400 --> 00:22:42.670
And so there was
this myth that it

00:22:42.670 --> 00:22:44.290
was about black
folks and white folks

00:22:44.290 --> 00:22:45.706
and poor people
and wealthy people

00:22:45.706 --> 00:22:47.546
holding hands and
singing "Kumbaya"

00:22:47.546 --> 00:22:48.920
and all feeling
good about living

00:22:48.920 --> 00:22:51.370
in the same community, when
it was really about how do you

00:22:51.370 --> 00:22:55.160
dismantle policy and
legislation that prevents people

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:59.510
from maximizing access to
the resources that give them

00:22:59.510 --> 00:23:01.510
the ability to have the
pursuit of happiness?

00:23:01.510 --> 00:23:04.410
But this narrative about that
integration piece I think

00:23:04.410 --> 00:23:08.547
has persisted because it allows
other generations to say,

00:23:08.547 --> 00:23:09.130
wait a minute.

00:23:09.130 --> 00:23:11.090
I was never supposed to
be about power for you.

00:23:11.090 --> 00:23:12.730
It was supposed to
be about you being

00:23:12.730 --> 00:23:17.010
able to get along in spaces
of other people's power.

00:23:17.010 --> 00:23:19.790
And when you're allowed to have
that integration narrative that

00:23:19.790 --> 00:23:22.360
continues, the
marginalized always

00:23:22.360 --> 00:23:24.400
feel comfortable
being marginalized,

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:26.720
and white supremacy
is able to persist,

00:23:26.720 --> 00:23:30.327
because it gives white folks
the gumption to believe,

00:23:30.327 --> 00:23:30.910
wait a minute.

00:23:30.910 --> 00:23:32.860
Integration was always
about these people

00:23:32.860 --> 00:23:35.500
coming in and being a part of
what we created and gave them

00:23:35.500 --> 00:23:36.420
access to.

00:23:36.420 --> 00:23:36.950
Hell no.

00:23:36.950 --> 00:23:38.074
That's not what it's about.

00:23:38.074 --> 00:23:41.590
It was about desegregation
to change policies and access

00:23:41.590 --> 00:23:44.130
to the very resources
that create power.

00:23:44.130 --> 00:23:46.210
And that's scary.

00:23:46.210 --> 00:23:47.290
And I'm sorry.

00:23:47.290 --> 00:23:50.280
Not just to white folks--
there are black folks

00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:52.170
that were scared of
that, because of how

00:23:52.170 --> 00:23:52.895
they had been conditioned.

00:23:52.895 --> 00:23:54.080
ROLAND MARTIN: [INAUDIBLE].

00:23:54.080 --> 00:23:56.250
JEFF JOHNSON: And because of
how they had been conditioned.

00:23:56.250 --> 00:23:57.810
And I'm not disagreeing
with Carmen.

00:23:57.810 --> 00:24:00.930
I'm saying that the
narrative of integration

00:24:00.930 --> 00:24:04.000
has persisted as the goal of
what civil rights was about.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:05.450
And that was never the goal. .

00:24:05.450 --> 00:24:06.960
STEVE PERRY: In the space
within which I work,

00:24:06.960 --> 00:24:08.560
which is education,
I often found myself

00:24:08.560 --> 00:24:10.250
fighting people to
get them to understand

