there's African;
there's indigenous,

00:36:38.710 --> 00:36:40.160
and there's European blood.

00:36:40.160 --> 00:36:44.440
But the European blood
isn't because-- we

00:36:44.440 --> 00:36:46.340
didn't have this love fest.

00:36:46.340 --> 00:36:47.740
There was wars. .

00:36:47.740 --> 00:36:50.960
There was the conquistadors--
Hernan Cortez--

00:36:50.960 --> 00:36:53.450
that came to Mexico
with black slaves,

00:36:53.450 --> 00:36:56.840
with black people that
he then made into slaves.

00:36:56.840 --> 00:37:00.520
And and so for me, when we
talk about Black Lives Matter,

00:37:00.520 --> 00:37:02.670
again, it is about power. .

00:37:02.670 --> 00:37:03.170
It's.

00:37:03.170 --> 00:37:05.390
About building collective power.

00:37:05.390 --> 00:37:07.790
There are leaders all
over this country.

00:37:07.790 --> 00:37:12.100
We don't have just the
Malcolm Xs or the Dr. Kings.

00:37:12.100 --> 00:37:13.780
It's a leaderful movement.

00:37:13.780 --> 00:37:16.510
But what we want is
liberation for our people,

00:37:16.510 --> 00:37:19.730
and we know that those currently
right now that are being

00:37:19.730 --> 00:37:21.100
oppressed are black people.

00:37:21.100 --> 00:37:23.580
And once Black Lives Matter,
then all lives matter.

00:37:23.580 --> 00:37:24.910
ROLAND MARTIN: Dr.
Stovall, you earlier talked

00:37:24.910 --> 00:37:26.000
about issue of power.

00:37:28.970 --> 00:37:32.240
It's very interesting when
I listen to Jesse Williams

00:37:32.240 --> 00:37:34.010
speak at the BET Awards.

00:37:34.010 --> 00:37:37.310
And when we
mentioned freedom, he

00:37:37.310 --> 00:37:39.570
said that freedom is
somehow conditional here.

00:37:39.570 --> 00:37:41.850
She-- meaning Sandra
Bland-- would be alive

00:37:41.850 --> 00:37:44.780
if she hadn't acted so free.

00:37:44.780 --> 00:37:46.532
It's interesting to
me when I go back--

00:37:46.532 --> 00:37:48.740
Jeff you and I have had this
conversation as well-- I

00:37:48.740 --> 00:37:53.790
go back, when I look at
more than three speeches Dr.

00:37:53.790 --> 00:37:54.750
King gave.

00:37:54.750 --> 00:37:57.070
If you look at the
three books he actually

00:37:57.070 --> 00:38:01.890
wrote-- numerous speeches--
he rarely ever used

00:38:01.890 --> 00:38:03.760
the word equality.

00:38:03.760 --> 00:38:08.670
He always spoke of freedom. .

00:38:08.670 --> 00:38:10.350
What's the difference?

00:38:10.350 --> 00:38:14.460
DAVID STOVALL: So I mean I think
when we talk about freedom,

00:38:14.460 --> 00:38:18.110
and this is an equality, and
this is the thing, right?

00:38:18.110 --> 00:38:22.722
So excuse this academic
thing happening.

00:38:22.722 --> 00:38:24.180
ROLAND MARTIN: You
are an academic.

00:38:24.180 --> 00:38:27.060
DAVID STOVALL: Right, right,
right, so they say, right?

00:38:27.060 --> 00:38:29.450
Existential philosophers
say that anytime

00:38:29.450 --> 00:38:31.150
you have a conversation
of equality,

00:38:31.150 --> 00:38:34.980
the assumption is that things
are never equal, right?

00:38:34.980 --> 00:38:39.000
And what that means is
when you're saying equal,

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:43.730
that's actually a term that is
actually assuming something.

00:38:43.730 --> 00:38:47.430
It is assuming that
everyone has the same things

00:38:47.430 --> 00:38:49.560
to get the same things.

00:38:49.560 --> 00:38:52.240
So when we talk about
an equal society,

00:38:52.240 --> 00:38:54.090
that's not necessarily equal.

00:38:54.090 --> 00:38:58.990
It's always who has what,
and who has the least, right?

00:38:58.990 --> 00:39:03.340
Freedom is the capacity
to self-determine.

00:39:03.340 --> 00:39:06.720
So when folks are talking
about their lives as mattering,

00:39:06.720 --> 00:39:09.500
they're talking about a
call to self-determination,

00:39:09.500 --> 00:39:12.070
a call that says
that my body is not

00:39:12.070 --> 00:39:14.900
the receptacle for
gratuitous punishment,

00:39:14.900 --> 00:39:19.090
that my body is not only my
own, but one that I can claim

00:39:19.090 --> 00:39:21.660
and one that I actually
can move in the world

00:39:21.660 --> 00:39:23.300
without persecution.

00:39:23.300 --> 00:39:26.600
So now, this difference
between equality

00:39:26.600 --> 00:39:30.390
is arguing that we all
need the same things.

00:39:30.390 --> 00:39:33.500
That is the worst assumption.

00:39:33.500 --> 00:39:37.210
Freedom says we have
to be courageous enough

00:39:37.210 --> 00:39:39.730
to say, not only do we
need different things,

00:39:39.730 --> 00:39:42.660
but we are willing to get
those different things

00:39:42.660 --> 00:39:45.190
on our own terms.

00:39:45.190 --> 00:39:48.020
And like Assata Shakur says,
freedom is something we

00:39:48.020 --> 00:39:49.590
don't know yet-- .

00:39:49.590 --> 00:39:51.880
we have a grand idea of.

00:39:51.880 --> 00:39:55.300
And it is something that
we pursue relentlessly.

00:39:55.300 --> 00:39:58.240
And in the relentless
pursuit of that freedom,

00:39:58.240 --> 00:40:02.230
we understand that our
bodies are in front of death

00:40:02.230 --> 00:40:03.870
all the time when
that claim is made.

00:40:03.870 --> 00:40:06.161
ROLAND MARTIN: Jeff, you
mentioned this relentlessness.

00:40:08.510 --> 00:40:12.830
When the remake of "Roots" was
shown on the History Channel,

00:40:12.830 --> 00:40:15.600
that opening scene
of Kunta Kinte going

00:40:15.600 --> 00:40:20.200
to the plantation-- he's
going, I only see three of them

00:40:20.200 --> 00:40:22.200
and 100 of us.

00:40:22.200 --> 00:40:25.236
How the hell are y'all
not taking them over?

00:40:25.236 --> 00:40:26.740
It was amazing to watch it.

00:40:26.740 --> 00:40:30.050
He was in this constant,
I'm fighting for my freedom.

00:40:30.050 --> 00:40:32.230
I just spoke at African
Arrival Day in Virginia,

00:40:32.230 --> 00:40:34.630
where the first slaves
came to Point Comfort, now

00:40:34.630 --> 00:40:36.752
Fort Monroe in Virginia--
this was on Saturday--

00:40:36.752 --> 00:40:38.190
where they recognize that.

00:40:38.190 --> 00:40:40.810
And we have the
400th anniversary

00:40:40.810 --> 00:40:43.340
of remembrance in three years.

00:40:43.340 --> 00:40:46.810
But this constant
fight for freedom,

00:40:46.810 --> 00:40:50.805
that's the piece I don't think
a lot of Americans, including

00:40:50.805 --> 00:40:54.160
black folks understand--
that since 1619, we

00:40:54.160 --> 00:40:58.370
have been in this constant
fight, every step of the way,

00:40:58.370 --> 00:41:00.020
whether it's siding
with the British

00:41:00.020 --> 00:41:02.690
in the American Revolution,
whether it's coming out

00:41:02.690 --> 00:41:05.370
with Emancipation Proclamation--
this constant fight

00:41:05.370 --> 00:41:08.490
for freedom.

00:41:08.490 --> 00:41:10.150
JEFF JOHNSON: And
I think, Roland,

00:41:10.150 --> 00:41:14.900
even in the examples
you gave, those

00:41:14.900 --> 00:41:21.150
are concrete examples of
institutional connection.

00:41:21.150 --> 00:41:24.430
The fight for freedom
wasn't always about joining.

00:41:24.430 --> 00:41:26.660
The fight for freedom
was remembering

00:41:26.660 --> 00:41:28.650
I wasn't created for this.

00:41:28.650 --> 00:41:30.560
So the songs that
I sing, the stories

00:41:30.560 --> 00:41:33.040
that I tell my
children, the hope

00:41:33.040 --> 00:41:37.700
that I give in this
ecosystem of hopelessness,

00:41:37.700 --> 00:41:39.800
was all about
fighting for freedom.

00:41:39.800 --> 00:41:42.970
And so, me helping you remember
your name, not the name

00:41:42.970 --> 00:41:45.250
given to you, but the
name that you have, me

00:41:45.250 --> 00:41:48.130
helping you remember
customs and creating customs

00:41:48.130 --> 00:41:50.330
so that you are not
subjugated to what

00:41:50.330 --> 00:41:54.350
they tell you can practice--
all of that was about freedom.

00:41:54.350 --> 00:41:56.940
So you didn't have to lead a
slave revolt to be fighting

00:41:56.940 --> 00:41:58.620
for freedom on a daily basis.

00:41:58.620 --> 00:42:01.250
The fact that you
existed, waking up

00:42:01.250 --> 00:42:04.480
realizing this was not
what God meant for me to be

00:42:04.480 --> 00:42:07.130
was a push towards freedom.

00:42:07.130 --> 00:42:10.820
I think the challenge, Roland,
as we talk about disruption,

00:42:10.820 --> 00:42:12.420
and we haven't talked
about this yet,

00:42:12.420 --> 00:42:19.060
is we haven't dealt with the
reality of the consequences

00:42:19.060 --> 00:42:20.840
of disruption.

00:42:20.840 --> 00:42:23.790
Not the consequences of
perceived disruption,

00:42:23.790 --> 00:42:27.840
because we had a whole lot
of professional disruption

00:42:27.840 --> 00:42:29.370
deceivers.

00:42:29.370 --> 00:42:31.100
ROLAND MARTIN:
Especially in this city.

00:42:31.100 --> 00:42:32.100
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:42:32.600 --> 00:42:34.330
ROLAND MARTIN: I'm
having a flashback.

00:42:34.330 --> 00:42:36.163
JEFF JOHNSON: There are
folks on television.

00:42:36.163 --> 00:42:38.400
There are folks in
organizations that

00:42:38.400 --> 00:42:41.440
are paid to be
perceived as disruptors

00:42:41.440 --> 00:42:43.720
but don't do any disrupting.

00:42:43.720 --> 00:42:45.792
But people remember and
they know the stories--

00:42:45.792 --> 00:42:46.625
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:42:46.625 --> 00:42:47.110
ROLAND MARTIN: See, if
this was an all-black room.

00:42:47.110 --> 00:42:49.229
this would be
happening right now.

00:42:49.229 --> 00:42:50.020
I messing with you.

00:42:50.020 --> 00:42:50.520
Go ahead.

00:42:50.520 --> 00:42:53.520
JEFF JOHNSON: So I
remember, because there

00:42:53.520 --> 00:42:54.750
is a political side of this.

00:42:54.750 --> 00:42:56.333
There's a social
justice side of this.

00:42:56.333 --> 00:42:58.780
But there's also a corporate
institutional side of this.

00:42:58.780 --> 00:43:03.780
And so I'm 43 years old and
remember the middle management

00:43:03.780 --> 00:43:07.160
thing that corporate
America did that created

00:43:07.160 --> 00:43:12.190
this ecosystem of black men that
could be in corporate America

00:43:12.190 --> 00:43:16.690
just high enough not
to feel marginalized,

00:43:16.690 --> 00:43:18.555
but not high enough
to control anything.

00:43:18.555 --> 00:43:20.180
ROLAND MARTIN: VP of
community affairs.

00:43:20.180 --> 00:43:20.860
STEVE PERRY: Always.

00:43:20.860 --> 00:43:21.859
Or the Dean of Students.

00:43:21.940 --> 00:43:23.690
JEFF JOHNSON: When I
worked for the NAACP,

00:43:23.690 --> 00:43:26.273
we had one question we used to
ask black executives, which was

00:43:26.273 --> 00:43:29.610
how many white
people can you fire?

00:43:29.610 --> 00:43:30.747
I'm serious.

00:43:30.747 --> 00:43:31.580
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:43:31.580 --> 00:43:32.780
JEFF JOHNSON: Because you
come with your big title,

00:43:32.780 --> 00:43:34.430
and you're talking about all
these people, you can control.

00:43:34.430 --> 00:43:35.000
ROLAND MARTIN: But do you
have P&amp;L responsibility?

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:36.940
JEFF JOHNSON: But if you
can't fire no white people.

00:43:36.940 --> 00:43:37.600
ROLAND MARTIN: There you go.

00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:39.725
JEFF JOHNSON: I'm not even
talking about the money,

00:43:39.725 --> 00:43:41.620
because you have black
pools of money, right?

00:43:41.620 --> 00:43:43.947
And so you got your P&amp;L over
your black people stuff.

00:43:43.947 --> 00:43:45.530
But if you can't
fire no white people,

00:43:45.530 --> 00:43:49.272
you really don't
have any importance.

00:43:49.272 --> 00:43:51.230
ROLAND MARTIN: Don't get
scared, now, like he's

00:43:51.230 --> 00:43:53.750
going to come fire you.

00:43:53.750 --> 00:43:55.520
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:43:55.520 --> 00:43:57.890
JEFF JOHNSON: Me and
boys used to joke

00:43:57.890 --> 00:44:00.780
that you could tell how
long somebody's dad had been

00:44:00.780 --> 00:44:03.460
in corporate America
by how little bass

00:44:03.460 --> 00:44:06.840
they had left in their voice
and how little facial hair they

00:44:06.840 --> 00:44:07.341
had.

00:44:07.341 --> 00:44:08.798
ROLAND MARTIN:
Damn, you said bass.

00:44:08.798 --> 00:44:11.362
JEFF JOHNSON: So there was
this piece where it was like,

00:44:11.362 --> 00:44:12.570
you roll up into the company.

00:44:12.570 --> 00:44:14.790
You're like, my name is Leroy.

00:44:14.790 --> 00:44:16.840
And I'm an intern
in the mail room.

00:44:16.840 --> 00:44:21.840
And then hey, my name is
Leroy, and I'm an intern

00:44:21.840 --> 00:44:23.400
in the finance department.

00:44:23.400 --> 00:44:30.100
Hello, my name is Leroy, and
I'm the CFO of this corporation.

00:44:30.100 --> 00:44:32.100
And we laugh.

00:44:32.100 --> 00:44:36.880
But I saw the emasculation of
black men in corporate America

00:44:36.880 --> 00:44:39.760
in the name of being
safe enough not

00:44:39.760 --> 00:44:48.610
to make other people
uncomfortable about the power

00:44:48.610 --> 00:44:53.100
that they brought just
by being black men.

00:44:53.100 --> 00:44:55.760
And the challenge that
I have is even now

00:44:55.760 --> 00:44:59.670
we don't talk about the
consequence of disruption.

00:44:59.670 --> 00:45:02.460
So we create the
perception of disruption

00:45:02.460 --> 00:45:05.820
to make people feel like we're
really pissed off about stuff

00:45:05.820 --> 00:45:08.660
that we're not pissed off
about, because we're not really

00:45:08.660 --> 00:45:10.790
creating the
disruption, because even

00:45:10.790 --> 00:45:13.650
those that want
to see the change

00:45:13.650 --> 00:45:16.500
are fearful of what has
happened to the disruptors.

00:45:16.500 --> 00:45:18.530
So whether it was Nat
Turner or whether it

00:45:18.530 --> 00:45:21.660
was that guy that was a middle
manager in this corporation

00:45:21.660 --> 00:45:24.920
that just got too black that
one day, and as a result,

00:45:24.920 --> 00:45:27.510
he was minimized or
removed or fired,

00:45:27.510 --> 00:45:31.040
or that guy that came every day
and had to cut off the goatee,

00:45:31.040 --> 00:45:33.470
because the goatee made somebody
else feel uncomfortable,

00:45:33.470 --> 00:45:35.650
or I dropped that
bass in my voice

00:45:35.650 --> 00:45:39.840
because my boss don't have it
in him, and as a result of it

00:45:39.840 --> 00:45:43.470
he's intimidated every
time I'm my authentic self,

00:45:43.470 --> 00:45:45.060
we haven't talked
about that enough.

00:45:45.060 --> 00:45:48.270
And so there is a generation
that, even within Black Lives

00:45:48.270 --> 00:45:51.930
Matter-- and Carmen, tell me
if I'm wrong-- is operating off

00:45:51.930 --> 00:45:55.220
of a perception-- not
everybody-- but too many

00:45:55.220 --> 00:45:58.130
are operating off
perceptions of disruption.

00:45:58.130 --> 00:46:01.920
They say, how do we create
what looks like disruption,

00:46:01.920 --> 00:46:04.890
but hasn't created
legitimate strategy that

00:46:04.890 --> 00:46:08.680
speaks to the dismantling
of institutions.

00:46:08.680 --> 00:46:13.040
That is risking more than
the perception of disruption

00:46:13.040 --> 00:46:13.630
is risking.

00:46:13.630 --> 00:46:14.747
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:46:14.747 --> 00:46:16.080
ROLAND MARTIN: Carmen, go ahead.

00:46:16.080 --> 00:46:18.530
But then, I'm going
back to Steve.

00:46:18.530 --> 00:46:19.522
Go ahead.

00:46:19.522 --> 00:46:20.230
Carmen, go ahead.

00:46:20.230 --> 00:46:20.780
Go ahead.

00:46:20.780 --> 00:46:24.620
CARMEN PEREZ: Oh, I
feel, as a disruptor,

00:46:24.620 --> 00:46:28.830
that the media perceives
certain individuals as leaders

00:46:28.830 --> 00:46:30.970
within the Black Lives
Matter movement based

00:46:30.970 --> 00:46:32.134
on their followers.

00:46:32.134 --> 00:46:34.050
You don't see these
individuals in the street.

00:46:34.050 --> 00:46:35.730
ROLAND MARTIN: Based upon
their social media followers.

00:46:35.730 --> 00:46:37.740
CARMEN PEREZ: Social media
followers-- Twitter followers.

00:46:37.740 --> 00:46:38.340
ROLAND MARTIN: Not
actual followers.

00:46:38.340 --> 00:46:40.160
CARMEN PEREZ: So
these individuals

00:46:40.160 --> 00:46:46.042
will get paid by corporations
to advertise whatever they're

00:46:46.042 --> 00:46:48.500
advertising on their shirts
while they're getting arrested.

00:46:48.500 --> 00:46:53.260
But I will say,
as a disruptor, we

00:46:53.260 --> 00:46:55.770
have several individuals
within our team

00:46:55.770 --> 00:46:58.720
in Justice League that have
different positions of power.

00:46:58.720 --> 00:47:00.125
ROLAND MARTIN: You just threw
a gut punch at Dr. Stovall

00:47:00.125 --> 00:47:00.375
over here.

00:47:00.375 --> 00:47:00.999
He's like, ooh.

00:47:04.280 --> 00:47:06.920
CARMEN PEREZ: And
we will look at how

00:47:06.920 --> 00:47:09.600
to not only dismantle,
but infiltrate,

00:47:09.600 --> 00:47:12.380
the systems that we're
trying to fight up against.

00:47:12.380 --> 00:47:16.890
So if I was a disruptor
here in Google-- I'm joking.

00:47:16.890 --> 00:47:18.600
I'm messing with y'all.

00:47:18.600 --> 00:47:21.250
I'm messing with y'all-- but one
of the things that I was being

00:47:21.250 --> 00:47:21.750
asked--

00:47:21.750 --> 00:47:23.155
ROLAND MARTIN: Security.

00:47:23.155 --> 00:47:24.530
CARMEN PEREZ: --I
was being asked

00:47:24.530 --> 00:47:27.480
to do is I was taught to
do system accountability

00:47:27.480 --> 00:47:29.190
from within the system.

00:47:29.190 --> 00:47:30.270
So I learned.

00:47:30.270 --> 00:47:33.420
I went into the criminal
justice probation department

00:47:33.420 --> 00:47:36.990
to learn the language in order
to then come out and give

00:47:36.990 --> 00:47:38.710
that information back
to the community,

00:47:38.710 --> 00:47:41.320
so that we could then hold--

00:47:41.320 --> 00:47:43.707
JEFF JOHNSON: The spook
that sat by the door.

00:47:43.707 --> 00:47:46.040
CARMEN PEREZ: And that's the
way in which my elders have

00:47:46.040 --> 00:47:46.990
taught me to do it.

00:47:46.990 --> 00:47:50.140
And then there's others that
will infiltrate, but then

00:47:50.140 --> 00:47:52.380
become that system.

00:47:52.380 --> 00:47:55.780
And I think that's what we
were trying to figure out,

00:47:55.780 --> 00:47:58.290
I think, sometimes, not only
in the Black Lives Matter

00:47:58.290 --> 00:47:59.875
movement, but in every movement.

00:47:59.875 --> 00:48:02.500
ROLAND MARTIN: It's interesting,
while I was listening to-- I'm

00:48:02.500 --> 00:48:06.830
coming to you Steve-- Jeff
talk-- I use this phrase

00:48:06.830 --> 00:48:11.370
a lot, parking lot militants.

00:48:11.370 --> 00:48:14.067
That's the folks-- oh, they talk
some shit in the parking lot.

00:48:14.067 --> 00:48:15.150
JEFF JOHNSON: E-gangsters.

00:48:15.150 --> 00:48:17.450
ROLAND MARTIN: Oh
man, but then when

00:48:17.450 --> 00:48:19.720
you go back in that building,
to Jeff's point, what

00:48:19.720 --> 00:48:21.890
happened to your bass?

00:48:21.890 --> 00:48:23.570
And so, Steve, while
he was talking,

00:48:23.570 --> 00:48:25.720
he was talking about disrupting.

00:48:25.720 --> 00:48:31.510
I'm literally sitting here
remembering me and you at CNN

00:48:31.510 --> 00:48:36.230
and remembering cats telling
you to cut your hair,

00:48:36.230 --> 00:48:43.400
because it was too
wavy, and remembering

00:48:43.400 --> 00:48:49.380
every show would get a readout
of voicemails that people left.

00:48:49.380 --> 00:48:52.170
In nearly every show, when I
was on Anderson Cooper's show,

00:48:52.170 --> 00:48:56.310
Paula Zahn's show, they would
come back and say, Roland,

00:48:56.310 --> 00:48:57.130
can you smile more?

00:48:57.130 --> 00:49:01.140
Can you smile more, because I
was kicking folks butts so bad,

00:49:01.140 --> 00:49:04.030
white folks watching
thought I was angry.

00:49:04.030 --> 00:49:08.620
Bill O'Reilly acting a fool
over here, and he's passionate.

00:49:08.620 --> 00:49:10.630
I'm passionate,
therefore, I'm angry.

00:49:10.630 --> 00:49:14.085
And I finally said,
if I smile anymore I'm

00:49:14.085 --> 00:49:16.310
going to be a damned mannequin.

00:49:16.310 --> 00:49:18.170
And so when you talk
about-- to Jeff's point

00:49:18.170 --> 00:49:20.610
about the flipside of
being a disruptor--

00:49:20.610 --> 00:49:24.190
the reality is, you will get
to the point where they say,

00:49:24.190 --> 00:49:25.330
all right. you know what?

00:49:25.330 --> 00:49:26.450
He too black.

00:49:26.450 --> 00:49:28.770
STEVE PERRY: So
there are disruptors,

00:49:28.770 --> 00:49:30.450
and there are commentators.

00:49:30.450 --> 00:49:34.090
And there are a lot of
people who are commentators.

00:49:34.090 --> 00:49:35.470
They can speak the speak.

00:49:35.470 --> 00:49:37.220
And they can present
themselves as if they

00:49:37.220 --> 00:49:38.890
are so radical and so focused.

00:49:38.890 --> 00:49:40.820
But asked them
ever, what have you

00:49:40.820 --> 00:49:44.485
disrupted other than a
conversation or dinner party?

00:49:44.485 --> 00:49:45.610
CARMEN PEREZ: That's right.

00:49:45.610 --> 00:49:47.680
STEVE PERRY: Like, what
really have you changed?

00:49:47.680 --> 00:49:51.090
ROLAND MARTIN: Did you ever
e-mail the CEO and push them?

00:49:51.090 --> 00:49:53.150
STEVE PERRY: There's that.

00:49:53.150 --> 00:49:58.000
One of the things I say,
typically, to African-Americans

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:02.340
who are on the come
up is live modestly,

00:50:02.340 --> 00:50:05.882
because too many
people who I know--

00:50:05.882 --> 00:50:08.340
they're laughing because they
know exactly what I'm talking

00:50:08.340 --> 00:50:10.720
about-- because the day
comes when your black ass is

00:50:10.720 --> 00:50:13.170
about to be asked to leave.

00:50:13.170 --> 00:50:16.660
And if you care too
much about this job,

00:50:16.660 --> 00:50:19.730
then you have to
shut your mouth.

00:50:19.730 --> 00:50:21.820
If you think of
yourself as somebody

00:50:21.820 --> 00:50:25.500
who sees this a job,
and the only way

00:50:25.500 --> 00:50:27.980
that you will live or
maintain this lifestyle,

00:50:27.980 --> 00:50:29.540
you have to be silent.

00:50:29.540 --> 00:50:33.370
To be a disruptor, you have
to accept you will be fired.

00:50:33.370 --> 00:50:35.060
You will be asked to leave.

00:50:35.060 --> 00:50:38.350
It is a condition of the
condition of those of us

00:50:38.350 --> 00:50:40.190
who feel compelled
to do something.

00:50:40.190 --> 00:50:43.120
I get so sick and
tired of people--

00:50:43.120 --> 00:50:47.050
god knows the
Twittersphere has made

00:50:47.050 --> 00:50:48.920
people think they're somebody.

00:50:48.920 --> 00:50:50.840
My sons yesterday were
taking me through all

00:50:50.840 --> 00:50:53.173
these different people who
are somebody on the internet.

00:50:53.173 --> 00:50:56.030
And I'm like, damn,
for putting makeup on?

00:50:56.030 --> 00:50:58.815
You got 47 million followers
because you arch your eyebrows?

00:50:58.815 --> 00:51:00.190
ROLAND MARTIN:
They beat, though.

00:51:00.190 --> 00:51:01.231
STEVE PERRY: That's dope.

00:51:03.590 --> 00:51:05.777
So the point is that there's--

00:51:05.777 --> 00:51:06.610
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:51:06.610 --> 00:51:09.950
STEVE PERRY: --this
entire group of people

00:51:09.950 --> 00:51:11.130
thinking that they matter.

00:51:11.130 --> 00:51:12.630
And people who think
that they think

00:51:12.630 --> 00:51:15.088
that they matter because they're
somehow connected to them.

00:51:15.088 --> 00:51:17.130
But at the end of the
day, can I run my hands

00:51:17.130 --> 00:51:19.170
across the building
that you built?

00:51:19.170 --> 00:51:21.670
Can I go to go sit down and
talk to the children whose lives

00:51:21.670 --> 00:51:23.350
you've actually influenced?

00:51:23.350 --> 00:51:25.540
This is not a esoteric
policy conversation.

00:51:25.540 --> 00:51:29.260
At some point,
there will be blood.

00:51:29.260 --> 00:51:30.120
There will be blood.

00:51:30.120 --> 00:51:35.100
I can tell you three weeks
ago, all four tires on my car

00:51:35.100 --> 00:51:41.360
were slashed-- all four.

00:51:41.360 --> 00:51:44.897
See y'all can have that other
conversation for other people,

00:51:44.897 --> 00:51:46.980
but you're not having a
conversation about whether

00:51:46.980 --> 00:51:50.290
or not you're going to have
an armed guard travel with you

00:51:50.290 --> 00:51:53.180
because you dared to stand up
for children for whom nobody

00:51:53.180 --> 00:51:54.610
else is willing to stand up for.

00:51:54.610 --> 00:51:57.280
Everybody else is willing to
watch them go into these failed

00:51:57.280 --> 00:51:59.574
schools and watch them
die incapable of learning,

00:51:59.574 --> 00:52:01.490
not because they're
broken, but because people

00:52:01.490 --> 00:52:02.864
keep convincing
them that there's

00:52:02.864 --> 00:52:06.660
something wrong with them
because they are not white.

00:52:06.660 --> 00:52:09.940
And so I'm telling you, you
ain't disrupting nothing

00:52:09.940 --> 00:52:14.170
because you changed some
conversation on Twitter

00:52:14.170 --> 00:52:17.060
so that you can find the next
white cop who did something

00:52:17.060 --> 00:52:19.630
that you find disagreeable
or because somebody

00:52:19.630 --> 00:52:22.060
at some college said
something-- always

00:52:22.060 --> 00:52:24.410
somebody on a college
campus hanging something

00:52:24.410 --> 00:52:25.120
in [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:25.120 --> 00:52:28.370
And everybody
trips the hell out.

00:52:28.370 --> 00:52:30.320
CARMEN PEREZ: I will
say, just to add,

00:52:30.320 --> 00:52:32.850
I think there's a
lane for everybody.

00:52:32.850 --> 00:52:34.300
There's a lane for everyone.

00:52:34.300 --> 00:52:36.550
There are those that
build the institutions.

00:52:36.550 --> 00:52:38.400
There's those that
work on policy.

00:52:38.400 --> 00:52:40.980
There are those that are
professional protesters.

00:52:40.980 --> 00:52:42.900
There are those
that are organizers.

00:52:42.900 --> 00:52:49.420
And one of the things that I
recently-- a lot of the work

00:52:49.420 --> 00:52:51.250
that we do is a
multi-pronged approach.

00:52:51.250 --> 00:52:54.060
I work, again, for the Gathering
for Justice and Justice League

00:52:54.060 --> 00:52:55.130
NYC.

00:52:55.130 --> 00:52:58.490
And ever since we
started working around

00:52:58.490 --> 00:53:01.910
the non-indictment
of Officer Daniel

00:53:01.910 --> 00:53:04.560
Pantaleo in the
killing of Eric Garner,

00:53:04.560 --> 00:53:06.470
you become a target,
because you're

00:53:06.470 --> 00:53:08.884
trying to disrupt something.

00:53:08.884 --> 00:53:10.800
ROLAND MARTIN: His point
with the tires, yeah.

00:53:10.800 --> 00:53:12.240
CARMEN PEREZ: You
become a target.

00:53:12.240 --> 00:53:15.720
And you get death threats.

00:53:15.720 --> 00:53:18.870
And you don't know-- you
get told by the mayor,

00:53:18.870 --> 00:53:23.510
you get a personal phone call
saying, you stop protesting.

00:53:23.510 --> 00:53:26.410
We put a moratorium
on protesting, right?

00:53:26.410 --> 00:53:29.150
And it's what you're
willing to do,

00:53:29.150 --> 00:53:31.520
and what you're
not willing to do.

00:53:31.520 --> 00:53:34.160
And so for me, it's
not about being silent.

00:53:34.160 --> 00:53:36.930
It's not about-- you talk about
the children and the lives

00:53:36.930 --> 00:53:40.720
of the people who you impact
because it's a life or death

00:53:40.720 --> 00:53:44.830
situation, not only for
them, but for yourself.

00:53:44.830 --> 00:53:48.240
Walking into prisons, you
get told before you walk

00:53:48.240 --> 00:53:50.790
in, and I've been doing
this for 20 years,

00:53:50.790 --> 00:53:54.370
we cannot negotiate your life.

00:53:54.370 --> 00:53:57.830
You got to understand that
you may not come out here.

00:53:57.830 --> 00:54:00.910
And what's interesting you
also have trolls, right?

00:54:00.910 --> 00:54:03.440
How many of you all got trolls?

00:54:03.440 --> 00:54:05.780
I've got plenty of trolls.

00:54:05.780 --> 00:54:09.940
I'm an executive director
of an organization.

00:54:09.940 --> 00:54:17.320
And because I don't compromise,
and I say anything that I want,

00:54:17.320 --> 00:54:20.210
I don't get certain funding.

00:54:20.210 --> 00:54:22.350
I don't get certain
sponsorships.

00:54:22.350 --> 00:54:24.950
We make miracles happen
with rice and beans.

00:54:24.950 --> 00:54:26.500
For me, it's about
relationships,

00:54:26.500 --> 00:54:29.390
me calling Roland Martin
to come and host my gala.

00:54:29.390 --> 00:54:31.300
He's like all right,
sister, I got you.

00:54:31.300 --> 00:54:34.140
That's what it's about for me,
because at the end of the day,

00:54:34.140 --> 00:54:35.864
I'm not going to
compromise, and I'm not

00:54:35.864 --> 00:54:38.030
going to sell out the young
people that I work with.

00:54:38.030 --> 00:54:40.270
But I will say it
comes with a price.

00:54:40.270 --> 00:54:42.270
And sometimes that's
a deadly price.

00:54:42.270 --> 00:54:42.900
JEFF JOHNSON:
Roland, real quick,

00:54:42.900 --> 00:54:45.530
because I think I want to build
on what Carmen was saying.

00:54:45.530 --> 00:54:49.450
I think that because so often
we talk about disruptors

00:54:49.450 --> 00:54:51.990
through the lens of the
most aggressive disruptors,

00:54:51.990 --> 00:54:55.640
we negate those that are
playing on different parts

00:54:55.640 --> 00:54:57.620
of the chessboard.

00:54:57.620 --> 00:54:59.940
I remember, again
from a corporate side,

00:54:59.940 --> 00:55:01.940
I was a black student
union president,

00:55:01.940 --> 00:55:04.090
and I'm raising
hell on my campus,

00:55:04.090 --> 00:55:06.800
and we're addressing some
fundamental policy issues,

00:55:06.800 --> 00:55:09.490
and I'm looking at my dad
who's in corporate America,

00:55:09.490 --> 00:55:10.510
like, he a sellout.

00:55:10.510 --> 00:55:12.280
He's just getting paid.

00:55:12.280 --> 00:55:17.220
And he was a VP
of Human Resources

00:55:17.220 --> 00:55:19.280
and head of Affirmative
Action at the University

00:55:19.280 --> 00:55:20.786
of Cincinnati.

00:55:20.786 --> 00:55:23.550
And I didn't
understand the stakes

00:55:23.550 --> 00:55:27.190
until the University
of Cincinnati

00:55:27.190 --> 00:55:29.760
got audited for federal
formative action

00:55:29.760 --> 00:55:32.060
compliance for hiring.

00:55:32.060 --> 00:55:35.560
They gave him falsified
numbers to sign off on.

00:55:35.560 --> 00:55:37.920
He filed an obstruction
suit against them.

00:55:37.920 --> 00:55:38.840
He got fired.

00:55:38.840 --> 00:55:40.870
He was all of a
sudden incompetent.

00:55:40.870 --> 00:55:43.510
And it was then that
I said, wait a minute.

00:55:43.510 --> 00:55:46.020
When my dad was here,
more people of color

00:55:46.020 --> 00:55:48.440
got hired than got hired
when he wasn't there.

00:55:48.440 --> 00:55:51.710
There was better relationships
between labor and management

00:55:51.710 --> 00:55:53.650
when he was there
helping negotiate

00:55:53.650 --> 00:55:54.890
than when he wasn't there.

00:55:54.890 --> 00:55:56.500
The people there
got greater benefits

00:55:56.500 --> 00:55:58.630
when he was there than
when he wasn't there.

00:55:58.630 --> 00:56:00.940
I was looking through
the lens of this really

00:56:00.940 --> 00:56:02.900
aggressive, grassroots,
mobilization

00:56:02.900 --> 00:56:04.970
model as the only model.

00:56:04.970 --> 00:56:07.680
He was walking through the
shadows in corporate America,

00:56:07.680 --> 00:56:09.920
ensuring that people's
lives were better.

00:56:09.920 --> 00:56:14.240
And he still got caught as a
result of when the time came

00:56:14.240 --> 00:56:17.820
to decide whether or not I'm
going to continue to play

00:56:17.820 --> 00:56:19.620
this subversive
game, or whether I

00:56:19.620 --> 00:56:21.250
have to stop them
in their tracks,

00:56:21.250 --> 00:56:23.540
he decided to be the
ultimate disruptor.

00:56:23.540 --> 00:56:24.600
And he paid the cost.

00:56:24.600 --> 00:56:27.930
Six years later, his case got
kick backed from the US Supreme

00:56:27.930 --> 00:56:30.380
Court to the Sixth
Circuit Court of Appeals,

00:56:30.380 --> 00:56:34.290
where he had to take a
settlement, because the judge

00:56:34.290 --> 00:56:37.750
hearing the case was an
alum of the university

00:56:37.750 --> 00:56:40.610
and a former associate
of the firm representing

00:56:40.610 --> 00:56:43.450
the university and
wouldn't recuse herself.

00:56:43.450 --> 00:56:47.670
And so at some point, no matter
where you play disruptor,

00:56:47.670 --> 00:56:49.690
you come up against
the realities

00:56:49.690 --> 00:56:52.690
of the systematic
oppression that's real.

00:56:52.690 --> 00:56:54.550
And so until,
regardless of where

00:56:54.550 --> 00:56:56.650
we are on that chess
board, whether we're

00:56:56.650 --> 00:57:00.022
chipping away at it by being
inside of these systems,

00:57:00.022 --> 00:57:01.730
trying to do what we
can from the inside,

00:57:01.730 --> 00:57:04.150
or we're outside
trying to push as hard

00:57:04.150 --> 00:57:06.150
as we can to crack
them from the outside,

00:57:06.150 --> 00:57:09.540
if we're not playing chess,
then at the end of the day,

00:57:09.540 --> 00:57:12.040
we're risking people
on the outside that

00:57:12.040 --> 00:57:14.499
are willing to be aggressive
without playing an inside game

00:57:14.499 --> 00:57:15.581
that's more sophisticated.

00:57:15.581 --> 00:57:17.940
ROLAND MARTIN: I mentioned
a couple of books earlier.

00:57:17.940 --> 00:57:20.500
I'm very much a
reader, and as you

00:57:20.500 --> 00:57:24.730
were talking about
disruptors, revolutionaries,

00:57:24.730 --> 00:57:27.223
who might look different,
immediately came

00:57:27.223 --> 00:57:33.070
to mind former staff writer
of the "Chicago Defender," who

00:57:33.070 --> 00:57:35.720
John Sengstacke,
sends to Michigan,

00:57:35.720 --> 00:57:39.120
takeover the "Michigan
Chronicle," Louis Martin.

00:57:39.120 --> 00:57:41.624
The book is called "Walking
With Presidents-- Louis

00:57:41.624 --> 00:57:43.540
Martin and the Rise of
Black Political Power,"

00:57:43.540 --> 00:57:45.300
by Alex Poinsett.

00:57:45.300 --> 00:57:48.530
And perfect example--
brother working

00:57:48.530 --> 00:57:52.780
in the Kennedy administration,
Johnson administration.

00:57:52.780 --> 00:57:55.370
Some folks said, man,
you selling out. .

00:57:55.370 --> 00:57:59.130
And what he's doing is placing
folks in different positions,

00:57:59.130 --> 00:58:03.700
advising the president,
literally affecting power.

00:58:03.700 --> 00:58:08.610
Bob Brown accompanied Coretta
Scott King to the airport

00:58:08.610 --> 00:58:10.280
to get Dr. King's body.

00:58:10.280 --> 00:58:12.580
Nixon hires him in
the administration.

00:58:12.580 --> 00:58:15.829
He had no designated portfolio,
but was doing exactly what

00:58:15.829 --> 00:58:17.120
you were saying to folks there.

00:58:17.120 --> 00:58:18.790
But how you work it with Nixon?

00:58:18.790 --> 00:58:22.330
He's saying, but this is
what I'm doing inside.

00:58:22.330 --> 00:58:25.590
So Dr. Stovall, getting
people to understand

00:58:25.590 --> 00:58:31.680
that this idea of being a
revolutionary and a disruptor

00:58:31.680 --> 00:58:33.600
looks totally
different depending

00:58:33.600 --> 00:58:36.700
upon what the goal is--
is it important for folks

00:58:36.700 --> 00:58:39.790
to have the conversations to get
a better sense of that person

00:58:39.790 --> 00:58:41.930
as an individual
to go, oh, now, I

00:58:41.930 --> 00:58:44.200
see what you're about, as
opposed to simply making

00:58:44.200 --> 00:58:45.210
assumptions externally.

00:58:47.930 --> 00:58:50.400
DAVID STOVALL: Real talking,
to be totally confessional

00:58:50.400 --> 00:58:55.130
about this, I was the worst
in assuming things of folks,

00:58:55.130 --> 00:58:57.160
in terms of their appearance.

00:58:57.160 --> 00:59:00.990
So in terms of seeing someone,
I'm like, man, that chump.

00:59:00.990 --> 00:59:02.070
I'll rock him the face.

00:59:02.070 --> 00:59:02.820
Man, come on, man.

00:59:02.820 --> 00:59:04.290
He playing with me, right?

00:59:04.290 --> 00:59:08.380
And what I really
didn't understand

00:59:08.380 --> 00:59:11.820
was actually, folks who
look like that actually

00:59:11.820 --> 00:59:13.350
got me into grad school.

00:59:13.350 --> 00:59:14.960
Real talk, right?

00:59:14.960 --> 00:59:18.190
And I think the other
thing to understand--

00:59:18.190 --> 00:59:20.030
and the point that
everybody made--

00:59:20.030 --> 00:59:23.350
if you have made any type
of commitment to justice,

00:59:23.350 --> 00:59:26.200
it is never if they are coming.

00:59:26.200 --> 00:59:28.770
It is when they are coming.

00:59:28.770 --> 00:59:30.810
So you have to be prepared
for when they come.

00:59:30.810 --> 00:59:33.270
And I learned that
from folks who

00:59:33.270 --> 00:59:36.190
may not have the same
type of disposition,

00:59:36.190 --> 00:59:39.980
but also who are very clear
about how they understood

00:59:39.980 --> 00:59:42.700
the justice condition,
because I think that there's

00:59:42.700 --> 00:59:46.119
many ways for us to approach
what the justice condition is.

00:59:46.119 --> 00:59:48.410
When you were talking, the
first person I thought about

00:59:48.410 --> 00:59:50.370
was Ella Baker.

00:59:50.370 --> 00:59:51.810
Ella Baker was very clear.

00:59:51.810 --> 00:59:55.020
ROLAND MARTIN: One of the
greatest unknown organizers

00:59:55.020 --> 00:59:55.960
in history.

00:59:55.960 --> 00:59:57.790
DAVID STOVALL: And
what did she say?

00:59:57.790 --> 01:00:01.250
We are the ones we
have been waiting for.

01:00:01.250 --> 01:00:04.870
So what does it mean to
actually move in that light,

01:00:04.870 --> 01:00:07.630
because the thing is always
now-- and I love Dead Prez.

01:00:07.630 --> 01:00:09.250
Used to say this
all the time-- I

01:00:09.250 --> 01:00:12.370
don't care what you come to
the revolution looking like.

01:00:12.370 --> 01:00:14.340
I just want you to
come to the revolution.

01:00:14.340 --> 01:00:15.850
You could bespoked up.

01:00:15.850 --> 01:00:18.170
You could have it fried,
dyed, laid to the side.

01:00:18.170 --> 01:00:19.620
You could have a bunch of locks.

01:00:19.620 --> 01:00:21.880
You would have a fro as big
as the one me and my pops

01:00:21.880 --> 01:00:22.421
used to rock.

01:00:22.421 --> 01:00:24.666
That doesn't even
matter, as long

01:00:24.666 --> 01:00:27.040
as you are there, and as long
as you are determining what

01:00:27.040 --> 01:00:28.730
is that justice as condition.

01:00:28.730 --> 01:00:32.270
Because if we are able to agree
on that justice condition,

01:00:32.270 --> 01:00:34.910
we can now figure
out the numerous ways

01:00:34.910 --> 01:00:36.850
to move to make sure
that it happens.

01:00:36.850 --> 01:00:39.391
ROLAND MARTIN: I know you all
are going to get tired of this.

01:00:39.391 --> 01:00:41.690
But I have this book too,
which is phenomenal--

01:00:41.690 --> 01:00:44.840
"Ella Baker and the Black
Freedom Movement-- a Radical

01:00:44.840 --> 01:00:47.000
Democratic Vision"
by Barbara Ransby.

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:48.458
DAVID STOVALL:
Right up the street.

01:00:48.458 --> 01:00:51.690
ROLAND MARTIN: To understand
Ella Baker continuum--

01:00:51.690 --> 01:00:56.140
progressive politics in the
'40s, NAACP field secretary,

01:00:56.140 --> 01:01:00.920
is SCLC creator, SNCC creatot--
that's a continuum there

01:01:00.920 --> 01:01:02.060
all throughout.

01:01:02.060 --> 01:01:03.662
We're going to go to questions.

01:01:03.662 --> 01:01:04.870
All right, we got microphone.

01:01:04.870 --> 01:01:07.027
Come on up.

01:01:07.027 --> 01:01:08.110
AUDIENCE: So Dr. Stovall--

01:01:08.110 --> 01:01:10.068
ROLAND MARTIN: You've
been taking notes, I see.

01:01:10.068 --> 01:01:13.560
AUDIENCE: I have
been You mentioned

01:01:13.560 --> 01:01:16.120
a definition of white
supremacy that I've never

01:01:16.120 --> 01:01:19.530
heard anyone articulate
in such an important way,

01:01:19.530 --> 01:01:21.570
and I think it's
really interesting.

01:01:21.570 --> 01:01:25.910
How do we support--
all of us-- how

01:01:25.910 --> 01:01:30.190
do we support what we're trying
to do here without raising

01:01:30.190 --> 01:01:34.190
the ire of that particular
group of people that are now

01:01:34.190 --> 01:01:36.470
out there supporting
people like Donald Trump?

01:01:36.470 --> 01:01:38.710
What's the balance, and
I think it goes back

01:01:38.710 --> 01:01:41.140
to your last point
of god, I'd like

01:01:41.140 --> 01:01:44.490
to find a way to do
this without alienating

01:01:44.490 --> 01:01:47.240
and sort of bringing out
the worst of the people who

01:01:47.240 --> 01:01:50.750
feel intimidated now by those
of us who want to change.

01:01:50.750 --> 01:01:53.155
DAVID STOVALL: Well, I think
this is the thing right.

01:01:53.155 --> 01:01:54.840
And thank you for that question.

01:01:54.840 --> 01:01:57.140
I don't think that
should be our job.

01:01:57.140 --> 01:01:58.620
And I don't think that we can.

01:01:58.620 --> 01:02:01.360
Because I think
the misconception

01:02:01.360 --> 01:02:04.930
is that we want to win
people over to our side.

01:02:04.930 --> 01:02:06.030
That's not it.

01:02:06.030 --> 01:02:09.360
The thing is we want to
recognize what this thing is.

01:02:09.360 --> 01:02:12.510
We can disagree about it, but
I want folks to understand

01:02:12.510 --> 01:02:14.510
how this affects folks.

01:02:14.510 --> 01:02:16.300
What does it mean
in the day-today,

01:02:16.300 --> 01:02:19.370
because this thing-- you can
argue all day with someone

01:02:19.370 --> 01:02:21.230
about their particular
disposition,

01:02:21.230 --> 01:02:23.900
but it's really this thing
around if you have made

01:02:23.900 --> 01:02:26.160
a conscious decision to
the justice condition,

01:02:26.160 --> 01:02:28.790
you have already become
confrontational before you've

01:02:28.790 --> 01:02:30.987
even had the conversation.

01:02:30.987 --> 01:02:32.320
I mean it's one of those things.

01:02:32.320 --> 01:02:34.650
I mean, it's not about
being appeasing to folks.

01:02:34.650 --> 01:02:36.770
I mean, I think that's
the mistake we make.

01:02:36.770 --> 01:02:39.750
It's not about being
friendly enough.

01:02:39.750 --> 01:02:42.000
It's like, look, this
is happening now.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:45.340
If we're really about
where we stand on things--

01:02:45.340 --> 01:02:48.790
and this is another thing,
once people reveal themselves,

01:02:48.790 --> 01:02:53.640
now you know how to move,
because once that person shows

01:02:53.640 --> 01:02:56.880
up, you say, OK,
that's that one.

01:02:56.880 --> 01:02:57.910
I need to go elsewhere.

01:02:57.910 --> 01:02:59.980
Here's the work,
because what we want

01:02:59.980 --> 01:03:02.050
to do, in this larger
justice condition,

01:03:02.050 --> 01:03:04.390
we want those folks to
show their ugly head.

01:03:04.390 --> 01:03:06.340
Now we know we're
dealing with right.

01:03:06.340 --> 01:03:09.590
It's harder with that
person smiles and now does

01:03:09.590 --> 01:03:11.210
the little passive
aggressive thing,

01:03:11.210 --> 01:03:13.080
and now the door is
closing, and they

01:03:13.080 --> 01:03:16.600
got two AK-47s waiting for you.

01:03:16.600 --> 01:03:18.430
So in Chicago, we used
to crack this joke.

01:03:18.430 --> 01:03:20.840
When you go to a
meeting with anybody

01:03:20.840 --> 01:03:23.400
in the city of Chicago, the
mayor's office or whoever,

01:03:23.400 --> 01:03:26.680
you have to understand that
there's a .38 on the table.

01:03:26.680 --> 01:03:31.890
As soon as you turn your back,
someone's brains is blown out.

01:03:31.890 --> 01:03:36.370
Walk backwards once
you leave the table.

01:03:36.370 --> 01:03:40.590
And that sounds extreme, but
this thing around when we get

01:03:40.590 --> 01:03:43.420
caught into that idea
around conversion,

01:03:43.420 --> 01:03:46.200
we obfuscate what
we're trying to do,

01:03:46.200 --> 01:03:49.780
which is to identify
how this affects folks

01:03:49.780 --> 01:03:53.310
and then what this justice
condition is, and now, how

01:03:53.310 --> 01:03:55.510
we are committed to pursue it.

01:03:55.510 --> 01:03:59.940
Because I believe that all
those folks will now start--

01:03:59.940 --> 01:04:03.500
we always like to use
this term-- self-select

01:04:03.500 --> 01:04:04.610
and go elsewhere.

01:04:04.610 --> 01:04:06.651
ROLAND MARTIN: We also
make the mistake, I think,

01:04:06.651 --> 01:04:10.190
of trying to make
everybody comfortable,

01:04:10.190 --> 01:04:13.209
when the reality is this
is all uncomfortable.

01:04:13.209 --> 01:04:15.000
STEVE PERRY: At it's
core, it's disruptive.

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:17.960
I mean, the expectation is
that the only way we will truly

01:04:17.960 --> 01:04:20.030
become the country
who we set out to be

01:04:20.030 --> 01:04:23.200
or the person that you set out
to be is to change your habits.

01:04:23.200 --> 01:04:25.430
The only way you're
going to lose weight

01:04:25.430 --> 01:04:28.060
is to change the way
you eat, increase

01:04:28.060 --> 01:04:30.580
your cardio, whatever it is.

01:04:30.580 --> 01:04:32.734
Change is by design disruptive.

01:04:32.734 --> 01:04:34.150
ROLAND MARTIN:
Well, first of all,

01:04:34.150 --> 01:04:36.350
you've got to acknowledge
that you want to change.

01:04:36.350 --> 01:04:37.870
STEVE PERRY: Well, there's that.

01:04:37.870 --> 01:04:41.090
But once you've done that,
once you've called for change,

01:04:41.090 --> 01:04:41.840
you have to do so.

01:04:41.840 --> 01:04:45.124
For instance, in
hiring, you have

01:04:45.124 --> 01:04:47.790
to look beyond the circumstances
that you typically look beyond.

01:04:47.790 --> 01:04:49.090
You have to look for
different skill sets.

01:04:49.090 --> 01:04:50.920
You have to be willing to
open your mind and heart

01:04:50.920 --> 01:04:52.830
through the fact that somebody
may look at the problem

01:04:52.830 --> 01:04:53.670
differently.

01:04:53.670 --> 01:04:55.140
And so they may
not be an answer.

01:04:55.140 --> 01:04:57.760
There may be multiple answers,
and as a result of which,

01:04:57.760 --> 01:04:59.750
you become disruptive
to the hiring practice,

01:04:59.750 --> 01:05:01.790
thereby creating an
entirely new conversation

01:05:01.790 --> 01:05:03.650
within your organization.

01:05:03.650 --> 01:05:06.260
And so it's not just
about-- one of the problems

01:05:06.260 --> 01:05:08.220
I have, for instance,
with the Democratic Party

01:05:08.220 --> 01:05:10.180
is this notion of diversity.

01:05:10.180 --> 01:05:13.144
Yeah, the colors were different.

01:05:13.144 --> 01:05:14.560
But they all got
up there and said

01:05:14.560 --> 01:05:17.570
some version of the same thing.

01:05:17.570 --> 01:05:19.600
So I didn't really
see diversity.

01:05:19.600 --> 01:05:23.130
I saw a different colored people
and some different genders,

01:05:23.130 --> 01:05:24.660
of course.

01:05:24.660 --> 01:05:29.040
But at the end of the day,
there wasn't true diversity.

01:05:29.040 --> 01:05:31.430
And so in order for us
to have the conversation

01:05:31.430 --> 01:05:34.870
around disruption, we have to
be comfortable with the idea

01:05:34.870 --> 01:05:36.590
that this disruption
is going to be

01:05:36.590 --> 01:05:39.184
at its core uncomfortable
for a spell.

01:05:39.184 --> 01:05:40.850
ROLAND MARTIN: It's
funny you said that,

01:05:40.850 --> 01:05:43.141
because Oprah Winfrey is on
the cover of the "Hollywood

01:05:43.141 --> 01:05:44.620
Reporter" Ava
DuVernay this week. .

01:05:44.620 --> 01:05:50.100
And Oprah says she has removed
diversity from her vocabulary

01:05:50.100 --> 01:05:52.670
because Ava has taught
her, no, forget diversity.

01:05:52.670 --> 01:05:54.170
We want inclusion.

01:05:54.170 --> 01:05:55.790
You want to be at the table.

01:05:55.790 --> 01:05:58.575
She said, not just diverse--
it's about inclusion.

01:05:58.575 --> 01:06:01.766
STEVE PERRY: And at the table
in a position where your voice

01:06:01.766 --> 01:06:03.140
matters as much
as anyone else's.

01:06:03.140 --> 01:06:05.306
There are times in which
I've been part of movements

01:06:05.306 --> 01:06:07.329
where they call me after
a decision has been

01:06:07.329 --> 01:06:08.620
made that we're having a march.

01:06:08.620 --> 01:06:10.660
And I'm like, what the hell?

01:06:10.660 --> 01:06:13.940
If I'm part of this,
shouldn't I been

01:06:13.940 --> 01:06:18.410
communicated with when you
were considering the action?

01:06:18.410 --> 01:06:20.840
Shouldn't my opinion
have mattered as much?

01:06:20.840 --> 01:06:23.610
See, inclusion in
that sense, is when

01:06:23.610 --> 01:06:26.090
my voice matters
as much as anyone

01:06:26.090 --> 01:06:27.880
else's in the conversation.

01:06:27.880 --> 01:06:31.460
And until such time as my voice
is seen-- at the start of this,

01:06:31.460 --> 01:06:34.660
I acknowledged that we don't
have a lot of women up here,

01:06:34.660 --> 01:06:37.860
because I think it's
important that it be clear

01:06:37.860 --> 01:06:42.000
that I recognize that, that
I'm not OK with the fact

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:44.900
that from a parity perspective
I'm calling and saying,

01:06:44.900 --> 01:06:47.080
what we need to do as
people, and I'm calling

01:06:47.080 --> 01:06:49.160
upon other people,
but on the same token

01:06:49.160 --> 01:06:52.580
not acknowledging
my own conversation,

01:06:52.580 --> 01:06:56.590
that we in this stage, if
nothing else, in diversity

01:06:56.590 --> 01:06:58.720
of thought, would have
a diversity agenda here.

01:06:58.720 --> 01:06:59.780
ROLAND MARTIN: Let's
go to questions.

01:06:59.780 --> 01:07:01.340
Of course, folks
who are watching,

01:07:01.340 --> 01:07:03.150
you can also ask questions.

01:07:03.150 --> 01:07:05.050
So it's Ana Turner.

01:07:05.050 --> 01:07:08.780
How can corporations best
participate in racial justice

01:07:08.780 --> 01:07:12.940
without undermining
existing social movements?

01:07:12.940 --> 01:07:13.630
Who wants that?

01:07:13.630 --> 01:07:16.010
DAVID STOVALL: There is
a great science educator

01:07:16.010 --> 01:07:18.180
by the name of
Jomo Mutegi, who's

01:07:18.180 --> 01:07:21.050
at the University of
Indiana Indianapolis.

01:07:21.050 --> 01:07:22.420
ROLAND MARTIN: You're going to
have to spell that one later.

01:07:22.420 --> 01:07:23.253
DAVID STOVALL: Yeah.

01:07:23.253 --> 01:07:25.720
And Jomo always
makes this point.

01:07:25.720 --> 01:07:28.390
He says, here's what you can do.

01:07:28.390 --> 01:07:33.360
He says, first,
you can apologize.

01:07:33.360 --> 01:07:42.230
Second, do not start to join or
make claims about a commitment

01:07:42.230 --> 01:07:45.460
to anything that you are
not willing to support.

01:07:45.460 --> 01:07:48.530
Third, get out of the way.

01:07:51.090 --> 01:07:53.490
So it's always
these things around,

01:07:53.490 --> 01:07:56.810
because a lot of times-- this
is a thing in education we often

01:07:56.810 --> 01:07:57.800
talk about this.

01:07:57.800 --> 01:08:02.400
The word help is temporary.

01:08:02.400 --> 01:08:04.590
We're talking about
solidarity, which

01:08:04.590 --> 01:08:05.710
is a very different thing.

01:08:05.710 --> 01:08:07.410
It is a more contested word.

01:08:07.410 --> 01:08:09.340
It means something different.

01:08:09.340 --> 01:08:12.130
It means that you
have agreed to support

01:08:12.130 --> 01:08:16.460
something that will challenge
you in the support of it.

01:08:16.460 --> 01:08:18.189
So now I think that
becomes important,

01:08:18.189 --> 01:08:23.010
because I hate it when I hear
folks say, I just want to help.

01:08:23.010 --> 01:08:25.370
We don't need that.

01:08:25.370 --> 01:08:28.029
I want to be clear about
that, because all that is

01:08:28.029 --> 01:08:31.090
is temporary, and all
that is a feel good thing.

01:08:31.090 --> 01:08:32.720
What we want folks
to do is to be

01:08:32.720 --> 01:08:35.340
able to challenge their
existence in this.

01:08:35.340 --> 01:08:37.510
We got to ask a different
set of questions,

01:08:37.510 --> 01:08:40.912
because I might even depart
at a different space,

01:08:40.912 --> 01:08:43.120
because when we look at the
language of this country,

01:08:43.120 --> 01:08:45.220
we see something
different, not just

01:08:45.220 --> 01:08:46.830
in the Emancipation
Proclamation,

01:08:46.830 --> 01:08:48.580
not just in the Constitution.

01:08:48.580 --> 01:08:51.960
We need to read stuff like
the Federalist Papers,

01:08:51.960 --> 01:08:53.180
particularly.

01:08:53.180 --> 01:08:55.330
Like Federalist Papers--
as [INAUDIBLE] talks

01:08:55.330 --> 01:08:58.430
about-- Federalist
Papers 2, 10, and 22,

01:08:58.430 --> 01:08:59.880
that talks about
the United States

01:08:59.880 --> 01:09:02.609
as being a country
in and of its space

01:09:02.609 --> 01:09:06.170
being preserved for white men.

01:09:06.170 --> 01:09:09.260
So now we begin to
ask those questions.

01:09:09.260 --> 01:09:10.399
It's not about us helping.

01:09:10.399 --> 01:09:13.300
It's how are we willing
to challenge ourselves

01:09:13.300 --> 01:09:17.080
in a very particular
way and then get out

01:09:17.080 --> 01:09:19.130
of the way to let folks
who have committed

01:09:19.130 --> 01:09:20.930
to do this work do this work.

01:09:20.930 --> 01:09:22.210
ROLAND MARTIN: And first, about
what you're laying out, also,

01:09:22.210 --> 01:09:24.510
about understanding that
you're understanding

01:09:24.510 --> 01:09:26.720
how the nation was
constructed, which

01:09:26.720 --> 01:09:29.390
means that you're understanding
the DNA of America.

01:09:29.390 --> 01:09:31.340
So when you actually
go through all of that,

01:09:31.340 --> 01:09:37.290
you can actually tie the
Federalist Papers to 2016.

01:09:37.290 --> 01:09:41.279
I just got an email-- and
he said it on Saturday

01:09:41.279 --> 01:09:43.819
when I was with him, Virginia
governor Terry McAuliffe,

01:09:43.819 --> 01:09:45.960
when he restored the
voting rights of 13,000

01:09:45.960 --> 01:09:47.229
formerly incarcerated.

01:09:47.229 --> 01:09:50.109
What folks don't realize is
the law that prevented them

01:09:50.109 --> 01:09:54.770
from voting was literally
based upon a legislator or 1902

01:09:54.770 --> 01:09:57.740
who said, this is to
keep darkies from voting.

01:09:57.740 --> 01:10:00.250
And he said, I'm
restoring these rights,

01:10:00.250 --> 01:10:03.880
because the law was based
on a racist premise. .

01:10:03.880 --> 01:10:07.930
But folks, in 2016, we're still
fighting to uphold that law

01:10:07.930 --> 01:10:11.680
but had no idea-- they
claim-- of the history.

01:10:11.680 --> 01:10:12.350
Carmen.

01:10:12.350 --> 01:10:14.010
CARMEN PEREZ:
There's also what's

01:10:14.010 --> 01:10:15.520
called Solidarity Summit.

01:10:15.520 --> 01:10:19.250
There's about 40 of us that
travel across the country with

01:10:19.250 --> 01:10:23.470
OSI-- Open Society Institute--
and the Ford Foundation,

01:10:23.470 --> 01:10:27.990
and we actually do some
really deep digging around

01:10:27.990 --> 01:10:31.380
our personal cultures and
do cultural exchanges. .

01:10:31.380 --> 01:10:33.130
And I think that's
also important to do.

01:10:33.130 --> 01:10:34.890
And when you look
at-- one of the things

01:10:34.890 --> 01:10:39.510
that I know in any institution
is usually I'm the only Latina.

01:10:39.510 --> 01:10:42.190
I'm the only woman.

01:10:42.190 --> 01:10:48.430
Or I'm younger than
everybody by 10 or 20 years.

01:10:48.430 --> 01:10:52.132
And so I will say that one of
the things that I've learned

01:10:52.132 --> 01:10:54.590
is that people will say, well,
it's because people of color

01:10:54.590 --> 01:10:56.160
aren't qualified.

01:10:56.160 --> 01:11:00.450
We don't have qualified
people, so that we could

01:11:00.450 --> 01:11:02.417
hire them to do this work.

01:11:02.417 --> 01:11:03.750
And I think that needs to shift.

01:11:03.750 --> 01:11:06.420
You were talking about not
just diversity in color,

01:11:06.420 --> 01:11:11.890
but also diversity in
age, diversity in gender,

01:11:11.890 --> 01:11:14.440
in different levels.

01:11:14.440 --> 01:11:16.730
But it's not just about
being at the table.

01:11:16.730 --> 01:11:19.250
It's the fact that when
you're creating something,

01:11:19.250 --> 01:11:23.080
bring those that are impacted
or those that you're actually

01:11:23.080 --> 01:11:26.080
looking to serve to actually
be a part of that conversation,

01:11:26.080 --> 01:11:27.170
like you were saying.

01:11:27.170 --> 01:11:31.240
But I know for me, one of the
things I constantly look at

01:11:31.240 --> 01:11:34.680
is am I taking up
too much space?

01:11:34.680 --> 01:11:38.210
Especially being a Latina in
a Black Lives Matter movement,

01:11:38.210 --> 01:11:42.700
or being an older person
working with youth,

01:11:42.700 --> 01:11:45.500
am I taking up too much space?

01:11:45.500 --> 01:11:50.130
And also, am I giving
individuals the opportunity

01:11:50.130 --> 01:11:53.140
and also supporting and
cultivating their leadership,

01:11:53.140 --> 01:11:53.670
right?

01:11:53.670 --> 01:11:55.950
And it's also about
relationship building.

01:11:55.950 --> 01:11:57.859
It's not about, like,
oh, you know what?

01:11:57.859 --> 01:11:59.400
You know, I don't
have black friends,

01:11:59.400 --> 01:12:01.940
so now I'm going to go
make some black friends

01:12:01.940 --> 01:12:04.850
and ask them every
race question.

01:12:04.850 --> 01:12:07.960
It's about you know
what, like I really

01:12:07.960 --> 01:12:11.510
want to be intentional
about who I'm talking to

01:12:11.510 --> 01:12:14.020
and who I'm building
relationships with.

01:12:14.020 --> 01:12:17.154
Go ahead.

01:12:17.154 --> 01:12:18.820
But I just kind of
want to offered that,

01:12:18.820 --> 01:12:22.350
just because I also know there
are white people that do this

01:12:22.350 --> 01:12:26.610
work around Black Lives Matter,
and there are white allies. .

01:12:26.610 --> 01:12:31.200
And sometimes they
take up a lot of space.

01:12:31.200 --> 01:12:33.670
They're the ones that are
showing up to the protest.

01:12:33.670 --> 01:12:35.810
They're the ones that
are doing the chants.

01:12:35.810 --> 01:12:38.930
And sometimes you gotta
remind them of their space.

01:12:38.930 --> 01:12:41.540
And I sometimes don't want
to remind all white people

01:12:41.540 --> 01:12:43.610
of where they need to be.

01:12:43.610 --> 01:12:47.510
What I will say is that
they'll be out there fighting

01:12:47.510 --> 01:12:49.020
for the liberation
of black people,

01:12:49.020 --> 01:12:51.436
but when you go to their dinner
table, ain't nobody black.

01:12:51.436 --> 01:12:53.370
So I just kind of want
to point that out.

01:12:53.370 --> 01:12:54.270
JEFF JOHNSON: Real
quick, Roland,

01:12:54.270 --> 01:12:56.228
because I think that
there are a couple things.

01:12:56.228 --> 01:12:58.920
One is I think companies
have the ability

01:12:58.920 --> 01:13:02.220
to do two really easy
things-- well, not easy,

01:13:02.220 --> 01:13:03.400
but pragmatic things.

01:13:03.400 --> 01:13:06.750
One is create ecosystems of
conversation that traditionally

01:13:06.750 --> 01:13:08.080
didn't happen before.

01:13:08.080 --> 01:13:09.730
And so how do you
create ecosystems

01:13:09.730 --> 01:13:10.740
versus echo chambers?

01:13:10.740 --> 01:13:13.700
So often within
institutions, people are just

01:13:13.700 --> 01:13:14.940
shouting at each other.

01:13:14.940 --> 01:13:17.580
Sometimes they're shouting
at each other in silence.

01:13:17.580 --> 01:13:21.870
So when two black men get shot
by police and police officers

01:13:21.870 --> 01:13:25.150
get shot, people may not
be shouting at each other,

01:13:25.150 --> 01:13:26.720
but they're shouting
at each other.

01:13:26.720 --> 01:13:29.460
So I know what side you're on.

01:13:29.460 --> 01:13:31.770
And we're walking by each
other in the hallway at work.

01:13:31.770 --> 01:13:33.470
And we ain't saying nothing.

01:13:33.470 --> 01:13:36.000
But I know you
support them cops,

01:13:36.000 --> 01:13:38.020
or I know you support
them black folks.

01:13:38.020 --> 01:13:41.227
And we're shouting at each
other, but nobody's listening.

01:13:41.227 --> 01:13:43.560
And so how can you be courageous
enough as a corporation

01:13:43.560 --> 01:13:46.310
to create ecosystems where
it's not about whether it's

01:13:46.310 --> 01:13:47.660
Blue Lives or Black Lives.

01:13:47.660 --> 01:13:50.300
It's how do we create
ecosystems in our firms

01:13:50.300 --> 01:13:53.720
that create space to have
difficult dialogue that

01:13:53.720 --> 01:13:57.915
doesn't become
judgemental or combative.

01:13:57.915 --> 01:14:00.160
And isn't about walking
away with agreement,

01:14:00.160 --> 01:14:02.160
because I think so often
these conversations are

01:14:02.160 --> 01:14:04.950
about do we walk away agreeing
versus do we walk away

01:14:04.950 --> 01:14:06.160
better understanding?

01:14:06.160 --> 01:14:08.790
The second thing is
how do we support

01:14:08.790 --> 01:14:12.870
the individual passions of our
employees without repercussion?

01:14:12.870 --> 01:14:14.810
And so as long as I'm
engaged in something

01:14:14.810 --> 01:14:18.330
that's not breaking
the law, can my company

01:14:18.330 --> 01:14:19.890
support me doing that?

01:14:19.890 --> 01:14:22.900
Third, how do we have
better conversations

01:14:22.900 --> 01:14:26.120
about the ecosystem of impact,
because, to Carmen's point,

01:14:26.120 --> 01:14:27.840
it's not necessarily
about Google

01:14:27.840 --> 01:14:30.990
showing up with Google shirts
at the Black Lives Matter rally.

01:14:30.990 --> 01:14:35.300
It's about where is
there an economic impact

01:14:35.300 --> 01:14:39.380
of a certain demographic of
customers of our corporations,

01:14:39.380 --> 01:14:43.290
and how do we engage them
in conversation or support

01:14:43.290 --> 01:14:45.810
in ways that are beyond
showing up at a rally?

01:14:45.810 --> 01:14:47.460
Where's the economic impact?

01:14:47.460 --> 01:14:49.840
And I think in the
movement, we don't always

01:14:49.840 --> 01:14:52.720
have economic impact-based
conversations.

01:14:52.720 --> 01:14:56.660
So where is the
social venture impact

01:14:56.660 --> 01:14:59.550
opportunities for companies
to say, wait a minute.

01:14:59.550 --> 01:15:02.040
I'm not going to be on the
front line of this movement.

01:15:02.040 --> 01:15:05.370
But I am going to support the
development of new schools

01:15:05.370 --> 01:15:08.320
that impact this community in
a way that reduces violence,

01:15:08.320 --> 01:15:10.280
because more opportunity
less violence?

01:15:10.280 --> 01:15:12.570
Or I am going to have
a conversation where

01:15:12.570 --> 01:15:16.120
why can't companies begin--
I'm confused about why

01:15:16.120 --> 01:15:20.890
in Chicago, there has not been
a public meeting of corporations

01:15:20.890 --> 01:15:23.510
about what's the economic
impact of violence

01:15:23.510 --> 01:15:25.794
to the city of Chicago,
where companies

01:15:25.794 --> 01:15:26.960
begin to say, wait a minute.

01:15:26.960 --> 01:15:30.420
We have a responsibility to
development of infrastructure

01:15:30.420 --> 01:15:31.780
and support in a city.

01:15:31.780 --> 01:15:32.910
I know I'm reaching.

01:15:32.910 --> 01:15:35.320
But what I'm saying
is she asked what

01:15:35.320 --> 01:15:37.950
were the potential solutions
of ways they can participate

01:15:37.950 --> 01:15:40.310
in racial justice
without undermining

01:15:40.310 --> 01:15:41.640
the existing social movement.

01:15:41.640 --> 01:15:43.090
Play your role.

01:15:43.090 --> 01:15:46.660
And your role is in the
impact of the economy.

01:15:46.660 --> 01:15:49.110
And so how do you do that
by having conversations

01:15:49.110 --> 01:15:52.980
with those that are impacted by
the economic impact of violence

01:15:52.980 --> 01:15:56.140
in Chicago or lack of
education in Baltimore.

01:15:56.140 --> 01:15:59.610
But I don't see those companies
feeling like they're invited

01:15:59.610 --> 01:16:04.280
or feeling the responsibility to
lead those discussions to talk

01:16:04.280 --> 01:16:07.600
about a whole another set
of ecosystem that impacts

01:16:07.600 --> 01:16:09.624
racial and social
justice without getting

01:16:09.624 --> 01:16:11.040
in the way of those
on the ground.

01:16:11.040 --> 01:16:13.373
ROLAND MARTIN: My answer to
this question is very quick.

01:16:13.373 --> 01:16:15.590
Before you decide
to get involved

01:16:15.590 --> 01:16:20.120
in some external movement,
look inside your company first,

01:16:20.120 --> 01:16:23.450
because it's just like my
biggest criticism of mainstream

01:16:23.450 --> 01:16:24.270
media.

01:16:24.270 --> 01:16:27.900
Mainstream media can't call
out the Republican Party

01:16:27.900 --> 01:16:30.280
when it comes to outreach
of black folks, when they

01:16:30.280 --> 01:16:31.800
don't outreach to black folks.

01:16:31.800 --> 01:16:34.830
And so it's very hard for
you to say, oh, no, no, no,

01:16:34.830 --> 01:16:36.090
we support that.

01:16:36.090 --> 01:16:38.940
But then when you look inward,
you go, oh, wait a minute.

01:16:38.940 --> 01:16:41.970
So when Reverend Jackson
targeted Silicon Valley,

01:16:41.970 --> 01:16:43.520
he said, you can't
have officials

01:16:43.520 --> 01:16:46.030
of Silicon Valley
writing checks that's

01:16:46.030 --> 01:16:49.330
supporting organizations, to
your point, wearing the shirts,

01:16:49.330 --> 01:16:52.610
but employing less than
1% of certain groups,

01:16:52.610 --> 01:16:55.740
and not just in science and
technology, when the reality is

01:16:55.740 --> 01:16:59.490
60% of all Silicon Valley jobs
don't even involve technology.

01:16:59.490 --> 01:17:02.560
It's your accounting firms,
law firms, advertiser firms,

01:17:02.560 --> 01:17:03.820
marketing firms.

01:17:03.820 --> 01:17:07.710
So any company, look at yourself
first before you go outside,

01:17:07.710 --> 01:17:09.090
because you might
get called out.

01:17:09.090 --> 01:17:10.890
Question here,
question here, then I'm

01:17:10.890 --> 01:17:14.190
going to another question
from an external audience.

01:17:14.190 --> 01:17:15.930
AUDIENCE: Thank you for coming.

01:17:15.930 --> 01:17:19.290
One of the things that I heard
that profoundly affected me

01:17:19.290 --> 01:17:24.260
from Tim Wise was that white
privilege is not about guilt,

01:17:24.260 --> 01:17:27.300
that white privilege is
about responsibility.

01:17:27.300 --> 01:17:28.990
And I think it's
tangentially related

01:17:28.990 --> 01:17:31.365
to what you were just talking
about-- that responsibility

01:17:31.365 --> 01:17:32.060
that we have.

01:17:32.060 --> 01:17:34.432
I'd love to hear your
thoughts about guilt

01:17:34.432 --> 01:17:36.390
versus responsibility
and that notion of trying

01:17:36.390 --> 01:17:39.080
to be comfortable, and
it's not possible really

01:17:39.080 --> 01:17:41.000
to be comfortable,
that we really

01:17:41.000 --> 01:17:44.110
need to be uncomfortable to
be able to be responsible.

01:17:44.110 --> 01:17:47.400
And that's not for our
own personal actions,

01:17:47.400 --> 01:17:50.549
but for what has happened in the
country and around the world.

01:17:50.549 --> 01:17:51.840
I'd love to hear your thoughts.

01:17:51.840 --> 01:17:53.030
ROLAND MARTIN: Two
folks-- tight answers

01:17:53.030 --> 01:17:54.280
in follow-up to that question.

01:17:54.280 --> 01:17:56.990
DAVID STOVALL: Super quick-- one
of the ways to actually engage

01:17:56.990 --> 01:18:00.940
that question is what
Brother Martin first said. .

01:18:00.940 --> 01:18:04.800
The conversation is far
with other white folks.

01:18:04.800 --> 01:18:07.320
Clearly this thing
around when you

01:18:07.320 --> 01:18:11.290
are engaging with other white
folks about what this actually

01:18:11.290 --> 01:18:13.860
means, then you get another
set of conversations.

01:18:13.860 --> 01:18:15.510
So in addition to
Tim Wise, check out

01:18:15.510 --> 01:18:17.650
a guy named Paul Gorski.

01:18:17.650 --> 01:18:19.900
He's committed to
doing this work.

01:18:19.900 --> 01:18:24.240
And then what he talks about
is that type of conversation

01:18:24.240 --> 01:18:27.150
is the in-house conversation
that other folks might not

01:18:27.150 --> 01:18:31.000
be privy to, But now will allow
you to think about how you move

01:18:31.000 --> 01:18:34.670
and what you do moving forward,
because a lot of times it's not

01:18:34.670 --> 01:18:40.120
about going into the guilt
mode around making folks

01:18:40.120 --> 01:18:42.970
feel halfway decent
that you now recognize

01:18:42.970 --> 01:18:44.630
what's happened to them.

01:18:44.630 --> 01:18:46.800
It's really around what
do we say to each other,

01:18:46.800 --> 01:18:48.295
recognizing this
thing to be true.

01:18:48.295 --> 01:18:50.170
ROLAND MARTIN: Another
person you mentioned--

01:18:50.170 --> 01:18:51.190
say the name again. .

01:18:51.190 --> 01:18:53.250
DAVID STOVALL: Paul Gorski.

01:18:53.250 --> 01:18:57.012
ROLAND MARTIN: Another person
you should YouTube is-- I'm

01:18:57.012 --> 01:18:59.690
trying to pull up her
name-- Jane Elliott.

01:18:59.690 --> 01:19:00.630
CARMEN PEREZ: Yes.

01:19:00.630 --> 01:19:01.650
Yes.

01:19:01.650 --> 01:19:04.090
ROLAND MARTIN: She did
this blue eye experiment

01:19:04.090 --> 01:19:08.700
on the Oprah show that
totally-- go look at her videos.

01:19:08.700 --> 01:19:11.160
And she goes right to
the heart of this issue.

01:19:11.160 --> 01:19:13.970
And she asks this question
of an all-white audience,

01:19:13.970 --> 01:19:16.590
how many of you
would trade places

01:19:16.590 --> 01:19:18.560
with a rich black person?

01:19:18.560 --> 01:19:20.640
And nobody raised their hand.

01:19:20.640 --> 01:19:23.100
She says that's white
privilege right there.

01:19:23.100 --> 01:19:25.470
And y'all ain't rich.

01:19:25.470 --> 01:19:26.171
Question.

01:19:26.171 --> 01:19:27.670
AUDIENCE: Thank you
guys for coming.

01:19:27.670 --> 01:19:29.580
This is really important.

01:19:29.580 --> 01:19:32.880
One of the biggest questions
that I have is what can I do?

01:19:32.880 --> 01:19:36.480
What should I do that
demonstrates solidarity not

01:19:36.480 --> 01:19:39.440
help, that is in the right
lane, that acknowledges

01:19:39.440 --> 01:19:43.582
that I am a white person, but
I still want to help with this?

01:19:43.582 --> 01:19:45.290
STEVE PERRY: Thank
you for your question,

01:19:45.290 --> 01:19:48.360
and I was waiting
for that question.

01:19:48.360 --> 01:19:51.520
I think that you
have to first do

01:19:51.520 --> 01:19:55.010
an assessment of your own
talents and interests.

01:19:55.010 --> 01:19:58.390
As Brother Johnson
said a little earlier,

01:19:58.390 --> 01:20:01.520
he talked about people
working in different spaces

01:20:01.520 --> 01:20:04.250
and the respect that we
have to have for that.

01:20:04.250 --> 01:20:06.900
And so whatever it
is that you think

01:20:06.900 --> 01:20:12.070
you could have an impact on
using your time and talents

01:20:12.070 --> 01:20:13.590
to make that happen.

01:20:13.590 --> 01:20:16.630
So for instance, if you
feel like your work was

01:20:16.630 --> 01:20:20.810
best with women, because
you're a woman, and for me,

01:20:20.810 --> 01:20:23.410
it would be about finding
an organization that looked

01:20:23.410 --> 01:20:25.030
to improve the lives of women.

01:20:25.030 --> 01:20:26.530
If it was about
writing about women,

01:20:26.530 --> 01:20:29.730
then you'd use your written
word to push that forward.

01:20:29.730 --> 01:20:32.720
I think any person that tells
everyone that they should do

01:20:32.720 --> 01:20:35.740
something in particular is
a person who's not learned

01:20:35.740 --> 01:20:38.260
and not compassionate and
doesn't understand that

01:20:38.260 --> 01:20:41.510
there's a beauty in the
intricacy of each one

01:20:41.510 --> 01:20:42.570
of our gifts. .

01:20:42.570 --> 01:20:45.710
And so I think what
we're tasked with

01:20:45.710 --> 01:20:50.110
is engaging your heart such
that your mind will follow

01:20:50.110 --> 01:20:52.410
and that you will use your
mind to think of the things

01:20:52.410 --> 01:20:53.220
that you could do.

01:20:53.220 --> 01:20:55.990
One of things I often think that
we all have an obligation to do

01:20:55.990 --> 01:20:58.130
is to involve
ourselves in what I

01:20:58.130 --> 01:21:00.860
refer to as
micro-political actions,

01:21:00.860 --> 01:21:02.710
meaning individual
tasks that will somehow

01:21:02.710 --> 01:21:06.880
improve the lot of
those people around you.

01:21:06.880 --> 01:21:09.670
And that may be something
as simple as volunteering

01:21:09.670 --> 01:21:12.710
on a school board
or working-- again,

01:21:12.710 --> 01:21:16.076
from my space-- with
children, to recognizing

01:21:16.076 --> 01:21:17.450
that at your
company there may be

01:21:17.450 --> 01:21:19.325
an affinity group, an
African-American group,

01:21:19.325 --> 01:21:21.360
or a Latino group, or
a gay straight alliance

01:21:21.360 --> 01:21:23.443
group, whatever the case
may be within the context

01:21:23.443 --> 01:21:25.580
of your company,
wherever you feel

01:21:25.580 --> 01:21:28.360
you could make the greatest
impact using your time

01:21:28.360 --> 01:21:31.192
and talents to do something.

01:21:31.192 --> 01:21:33.150
Other people are not
going to get caught up in,

01:21:33.150 --> 01:21:35.620
let's say, something that
is political and a big P

01:21:35.620 --> 01:21:36.560
political.

01:21:36.560 --> 01:21:38.530
Whereas, some people
may say, I don't

01:21:38.530 --> 01:21:40.530
want you to think that
because you did something

01:21:40.530 --> 01:21:43.880
at Google that that would
somehow be less than important.

01:21:43.880 --> 01:21:47.980
I would suggest to you that
there's a lot that you can do.

01:21:47.980 --> 01:21:50.770
It starts with you taking
an inventory, doing

01:21:50.770 --> 01:21:54.220
an audit of your time,
talents, and desires,

01:21:54.220 --> 01:21:57.422
and with all due haste,
not waiting another day,

01:21:57.422 --> 01:21:59.630
because I'll say this final
thing-- the fact that you

01:21:59.630 --> 01:22:02.070
guys are here is dope.

01:22:02.070 --> 01:22:03.597
And I say that
sincerely because I'm

01:22:03.597 --> 01:22:05.430
sure that they're going
to pay you no matter

01:22:05.430 --> 01:22:06.679
where you are in the building.

01:22:10.080 --> 01:22:13.870
But based upon the food that was
coming out of a sick cafeteria

01:22:13.870 --> 01:22:16.480
that you seem to have, y'all
could have spent a little more

01:22:16.480 --> 01:22:17.930
time there.

01:22:17.930 --> 01:22:20.720
The fact that you're
here leads me to believe

01:22:20.720 --> 01:22:22.430
that you want to do something.

01:22:22.430 --> 01:22:23.900
You want to be inspired.

01:22:23.900 --> 01:22:26.850
You want to find the
space in which you fit in.

01:22:26.850 --> 01:22:29.890
And the challenge that I
know that I have at times

01:22:29.890 --> 01:22:32.450
is, I want to answer your
question like in the way

01:22:32.450 --> 01:22:34.820
that I think you want it
answered, like a specific,

01:22:34.820 --> 01:22:37.360
you should tomorrow
morning go here.

01:22:37.360 --> 01:22:38.990
But I don't know
the answer to that.

01:22:38.990 --> 01:22:43.080
But I do know tonight,
on your ride home,

01:22:43.080 --> 01:22:45.530
you can come up with a
solution, because that thing

01:22:45.530 --> 01:22:47.220
that's been peeing
inside your heart

01:22:47.220 --> 01:22:49.710
that you should do--
not should anymore.

01:22:49.710 --> 01:22:50.847
It's must.

01:22:50.847 --> 01:22:51.680
ROLAND MARTIN: Jeff.

01:22:51.680 --> 01:22:52.721
JEFF JOHNSON: Real quick.

01:22:52.721 --> 01:22:55.310
The other thing I
would say is listen,

01:22:55.310 --> 01:22:57.520
because I think a lot
of us in our desire

01:22:57.520 --> 01:23:02.430
to do good bring too many
assumptions to that process.

01:23:02.430 --> 01:23:04.970
I'll never forget taking a
bunch of college students

01:23:04.970 --> 01:23:07.880
to New Orleans
right after Katrina.

01:23:07.880 --> 01:23:11.110
And they were
incredibly well-meaning,

01:23:11.110 --> 01:23:14.220
but unbelievably arrogant.

01:23:14.220 --> 01:23:19.890
They thought they were saving
somebody on their spring break.

01:23:19.890 --> 01:23:23.300
And we had to tell them
before they engaged,

01:23:23.300 --> 01:23:25.390
the most important thing
you can do tomorrow

01:23:25.390 --> 01:23:28.590
is listen to what the
people tell you to do,

01:23:28.590 --> 01:23:30.830
because they already
have the answers.

01:23:30.830 --> 01:23:33.410
And if you are going to be
in solidarity with them,

01:23:33.410 --> 01:23:35.760
it's not about you coming
in with your brilliance

01:23:35.760 --> 01:23:37.610
to tell them what they need.

01:23:37.610 --> 01:23:41.610
It's your humility coupled
with your brilliance that can

01:23:41.610 --> 01:23:42.937
be directed in the right way.

01:23:42.937 --> 01:23:45.270
ROLAND MARTIN: When we mentioned
the Barbara Ransby book

01:23:45.270 --> 01:23:47.720
on Ella Baker, that
was the one thing

01:23:47.720 --> 01:23:51.420
she told everyone at the
NAACP, SCLC, and the SNCC.

01:23:51.420 --> 01:23:52.795
She said, when
you go to Alabama,

01:23:52.795 --> 01:23:55.110
and you're going to those
sharecroppers, first of all,

01:23:55.110 --> 01:23:57.792
take off your damn college
clothes and put a overall on.

01:23:57.792 --> 01:24:01.086
And she said, and
listen to them.

01:24:01.086 --> 01:24:02.460
Forget the fact
that some of them

01:24:02.460 --> 01:24:04.360
have a third and
fourth grade education.

01:24:04.360 --> 01:24:07.910
She said, let them tell you what
they want to do and then say,

01:24:07.910 --> 01:24:09.660
I'm here to help
you achieve that.

