01:33:40.980 --> 01:33:41.680
DAVID STOVALL:
Just something real

01:33:41.680 --> 01:33:43.096
quick around this
thing around it.

01:33:43.096 --> 01:33:44.930
We made depart on
this moment, but I

01:33:44.930 --> 01:33:49.960
want us to be clear about
when we talk about education,

01:33:49.960 --> 01:33:54.090
there is an assumption
that is very dangerous.

01:33:54.090 --> 01:33:56.570
One of the assumptions
that is very dangerous

01:33:56.570 --> 01:34:01.270
is that education works like
you all do in businesses.

01:34:01.270 --> 01:34:04.160
And this is why it's dangerous.

01:34:04.160 --> 01:34:09.870
Models of efficiency tell us
that we can do a lot of things

01:34:09.870 --> 01:34:12.790
very well and sanguine.

01:34:12.790 --> 01:34:15.740
We don't learn like that.

01:34:15.740 --> 01:34:22.580
So education can be effective,
but it's not always efficient

01:34:22.580 --> 01:34:24.870
in the general
sense of efficiency.

01:34:24.870 --> 01:34:29.290
And I think there's a common
assumption or misconception

01:34:29.290 --> 01:34:32.360
that if something is working
smoothly, that it's working.

01:34:32.360 --> 01:34:34.600
That is not the case.

01:34:34.600 --> 01:34:38.570
We have to have spaces
that support young folks

01:34:38.570 --> 01:34:42.520
in the ways in which
they learn, because this

01:34:42.520 --> 01:34:46.170
is a big contention,
because a lot of times folks

01:34:46.170 --> 01:34:49.990
can drop in communities and
say, here's this new thing.

01:34:49.990 --> 01:34:51.920
And you've had a ton of shit.

01:34:51.920 --> 01:34:53.090
And here's this new thing.

01:34:53.090 --> 01:34:56.212
But all it really is new. .

01:34:56.212 --> 01:34:58.420
They haven't talked about
what this thing is actually

01:34:58.420 --> 01:34:59.600
putting forward.

01:34:59.600 --> 01:35:03.130
So a lot of times you get these
situations where families,

01:35:03.130 --> 01:35:06.330
their desperation is played
on, and opposed to saying,

01:35:06.330 --> 01:35:09.440
here's what we're going to
do in partnership with you,

01:35:09.440 --> 01:35:11.600
it's opposed to you've had shit.

01:35:11.600 --> 01:35:12.579
Here's this new thing.

01:35:12.579 --> 01:35:13.120
I don't know.

01:35:13.120 --> 01:35:15.470
It's at least not that
thing that you've had.

01:35:15.470 --> 01:35:17.750
And I think that thing
becomes critically important

01:35:17.750 --> 01:35:20.630
when we talk about
educational spaces,

01:35:20.630 --> 01:35:23.570
because that piece
around being affective

01:35:23.570 --> 01:35:26.670
based on the community's
needs is critical.

01:35:26.670 --> 01:35:30.395
Anything else is a projection
of the larger colonial project.

01:35:30.395 --> 01:35:32.020
STEVE PERRY: I think
one of the things,

01:35:32.020 --> 01:35:34.890
also, to keep in mind as we
have that conversation is

01:35:34.890 --> 01:35:38.380
that the reason why parents
are running screaming

01:35:38.380 --> 01:35:40.510
from these schools is
because in many cases

01:35:40.510 --> 01:35:42.536
they went to those
schools as well.

01:35:42.536 --> 01:35:44.410
And their grandparents
went to those schools.

01:35:44.410 --> 01:35:47.120
And they were
under-served by them.

01:35:47.120 --> 01:35:50.900
And so no one should
consider opening anything,

01:35:50.900 --> 01:35:53.530
whether it be any
type of organization

01:35:53.530 --> 01:35:55.720
in a community that doesn't
take into consideration

01:35:55.720 --> 01:35:57.290
the integrity of the community.

01:35:57.290 --> 01:36:01.890
On the same token, no one
should also stop the parents

01:36:01.890 --> 01:36:04.990
from doing what
they must do to go

01:36:04.990 --> 01:36:06.246
to the best schools they can.

01:36:06.246 --> 01:36:08.370
There are children who have
attended my schools who

01:36:08.370 --> 01:36:11.160
I know for a fact do not
live in the catchment areas.

01:36:11.160 --> 01:36:12.400
I know it.

01:36:12.400 --> 01:36:14.700
I know they're using
somebody else's address,

01:36:14.700 --> 01:36:17.420
and I will never tell.

01:36:17.420 --> 01:36:21.290
It is not going to happen,
because I'd rather them break

01:36:21.290 --> 01:36:24.740
a law that is unjust than to do
something as unjust as to put

01:36:24.740 --> 01:36:26.470
abide by the law.

01:36:26.470 --> 01:36:29.670
We have a set of laws that have
been put in place that started

01:36:29.670 --> 01:36:32.460
with the various segregation
of neighborhoods,

01:36:32.460 --> 01:36:35.120
the creation of ghettos,
that have fostered

01:36:35.120 --> 01:36:38.270
the failures of
millions, literally

01:36:38.270 --> 01:36:43.090
millions, of children-- millions
who've done nothing wrong other

01:36:43.090 --> 01:36:45.470
than to be born in
the wrong zip code.

01:36:45.470 --> 01:36:48.360
And so what we hear too
often in the conversation

01:36:48.360 --> 01:36:52.100
around education is
about employment.

01:36:52.100 --> 01:36:55.030
We do not hear
about the children.

01:36:55.030 --> 01:36:58.540
And you you'll hear diversionary
tactics about testing

01:36:58.540 --> 01:37:02.210
and privatization and other
notions that somehow are meant

01:37:02.210 --> 01:37:04.170
to take your eye off the ball.

01:37:04.170 --> 01:37:06.490
But at the end of the
day, if you are so blessed

01:37:06.490 --> 01:37:09.191
to be a parent, you will
pray the same prayer

01:37:09.191 --> 01:37:11.440
over your children that every
single person has prayed

01:37:11.440 --> 01:37:14.250
regardless of religion or type--
that your child does better

01:37:14.250 --> 01:37:14.982
than you.

01:37:14.982 --> 01:37:17.190
And one of the most important
things that you will do

01:37:17.190 --> 01:37:20.020
is to decide on the school
that they will attend.

01:37:20.020 --> 01:37:25.250
And we have seen these schools
fail-- great, fantastic,

01:37:25.250 --> 01:37:27.310
amazing, teachers
in some of them,

01:37:27.310 --> 01:37:30.240
fantastic principals
in some of them.

01:37:30.240 --> 01:37:34.340
But for whatever the case
may be, they're not winning.

01:37:34.340 --> 01:37:40.050
And I, for one, would never want
to be even slightly responsible

01:37:40.050 --> 01:37:42.210
for keeping in place
any policies that

01:37:42.210 --> 01:37:45.530
will send one child one
day to a failed school.

01:37:45.530 --> 01:37:48.470
I'll say this final point.

01:37:48.470 --> 01:37:51.430
Of the hardest things to see--
and anybody up who's ever

01:37:51.430 --> 01:37:55.400
seen this knows this--
is the see a child who's

01:37:55.400 --> 01:37:59.030
given up on school,
the dead stare

01:37:59.030 --> 01:38:01.580
that comes over the face of a
seventh grader who recognizes

01:38:01.580 --> 01:38:05.400
that there's just no hope for
her or him in this institution,

01:38:05.400 --> 01:38:07.260
and that they have
in fact essentially

01:38:07.260 --> 01:38:10.780
been broken-- intentionally
broken, so much so

01:38:10.780 --> 01:38:14.890
that their self-esteem is shot,
versus the time when you see

01:38:14.890 --> 01:38:16.850
the child who's four
or five years old

01:38:16.850 --> 01:38:20.600
who's super-duper excited
about school, just

01:38:20.600 --> 01:38:25.430
can't wait to come
to school and learn.

01:38:25.430 --> 01:38:29.090
Why is it that we would ever
keep in place an institution

01:38:29.090 --> 01:38:33.060
that has promised to destroy
the children most in need--

01:38:33.060 --> 01:38:35.710
black, Latino, poor, more
specifically, African-American

01:38:35.710 --> 01:38:36.210
boys?

01:38:36.210 --> 01:38:39.050
Why would we ever send
another human being to that

01:38:39.050 --> 01:38:41.519
and call ourselves
a humane society?

01:38:41.519 --> 01:38:42.560
It's not about resources.

01:38:42.560 --> 01:38:44.270
It's not about how
much a school costs,

01:38:44.270 --> 01:38:47.260
because we spend the most
amount of resources locking

01:38:47.260 --> 01:38:50.420
those very same little boys up.

01:38:50.420 --> 01:38:55.480
The issue is about the quality
of the institution, which

01:38:55.480 --> 01:38:59.570
starts with a respect for
the community, no doubt,

01:38:59.570 --> 01:39:02.380
but also the anticipation
that every single child who's

01:39:02.380 --> 01:39:04.374
in the building is
fricken amazing,

01:39:04.374 --> 01:39:05.790
and they're going
to do everything

01:39:05.790 --> 01:39:07.950
they can to make that possible.

01:39:07.950 --> 01:39:10.616
CARMEN PEREZ: I just wanted
to add a cost analysis to what

01:39:10.616 --> 01:39:11.740
he was saying, in regards--

01:39:11.740 --> 01:39:13.030
ROLAND MARTIN: This is going
to be your final comment.

01:39:13.030 --> 01:39:14.300
CARMEN PEREZ: Yeah, sorry.

01:39:14.300 --> 01:39:18.640
It cost $125,000
in New York state

01:39:18.640 --> 01:39:23.730
to lock a young person up per
year, versus $10,000 from K

01:39:23.730 --> 01:39:26.950
to 12 to educate them.

01:39:26.950 --> 01:39:30.330
So I just wanted to-- because
what he's talking about

01:39:30.330 --> 01:39:33.620
is providing education
opportunities for young people

01:39:33.620 --> 01:39:35.950
so that they could thrive
and not end up in the system

01:39:35.950 --> 01:39:39.330
that I'm working in and seen
those young people at my table.

01:39:39.330 --> 01:39:43.100
And so we see young people--
as young as 10 years old--

01:39:43.100 --> 01:39:46.950
incarcerated in a
detention center.

01:39:46.950 --> 01:39:49.140
And the clothes
doesn't even fit them.

01:39:49.140 --> 01:39:51.900
And it's because they
don't have anything else.

01:39:51.900 --> 01:39:53.190
They don't have hope anymore.

01:39:53.190 --> 01:39:54.690
DAVID STOVALL: And
let us not forget

01:39:54.690 --> 01:39:57.469
the rising number of
young girls of color who

01:39:57.469 --> 01:39:58.510
are in those institutes--

01:39:58.510 --> 01:39:59.760
STEVE PERRY: It's frightening.

01:39:59.760 --> 01:40:01.970
DAVID STOVAL: It's critical,
because that population

01:40:01.970 --> 01:40:04.060
has actually increased
300% since 1970.

01:40:04.060 --> 01:40:05.810
STEVE PERRY: It's not
slowing down at all.

01:40:05.810 --> 01:40:07.240
CARMEN PEREZ: 500.

01:40:07.240 --> 01:40:11.062
DAVID STOVALL: So we have
to put that on the table.

01:40:11.062 --> 01:40:12.770
ROLAND MARTIN: That's
your final comment?

01:40:12.770 --> 01:40:13.170
DAVID STOVALL: Yes, sir

01:40:13.170 --> 01:40:15.320
ROLAND MARTIN: Jeff Johnson,
you can close us out.

01:40:15.320 --> 01:40:17.910
JEFF JOHNSON: Great book--
"Why Should White Guys Have

01:40:17.910 --> 01:40:24.350
All the Fun?" by Reginald
F. Lewis, first person

01:40:24.350 --> 01:40:27.930
to negotiate a billion dollar
deal in corporate America,

01:40:27.930 --> 01:40:31.760
and speaks a lot about what
we've been talking about today.

01:40:31.760 --> 01:40:33.670
Second of all, I
don't want to leave

01:40:33.670 --> 01:40:35.580
without-- there's a
question up here that

01:40:35.580 --> 01:40:37.954
says is it possible that women
are under-represented here

01:40:37.954 --> 01:40:39.470
because the language
of disruption

01:40:39.470 --> 01:40:41.570
and maybe the movement
isn't inclusive?

01:40:41.570 --> 01:40:44.850
There was discussion about
mid-level, mid-tier corporate

01:40:44.850 --> 01:40:46.710
jobs for black men
being emasculating,

01:40:46.710 --> 01:40:49.150
but where do black women
fit into that conversation?

01:40:49.150 --> 01:40:51.320
Simple answer is yes.

01:40:51.320 --> 01:40:56.000
And I think Carmen and
others, many in this room,

01:40:56.000 --> 01:41:00.630
have been fighting feverishly
to make sure that we challenge,

01:41:00.630 --> 01:41:03.610
I think, some of the sexism
and misogyny that existed

01:41:03.610 --> 01:41:06.560
within civil rights and
the black power movements

01:41:06.560 --> 01:41:08.660
from a people of
color perspective,

01:41:08.660 --> 01:41:12.970
but broadly as it relates to
movements for social change.

01:41:12.970 --> 01:41:14.900
And we're constantly
challenging it.

01:41:14.900 --> 01:41:16.960
And even us bringing
it up in the beginning,

01:41:16.960 --> 01:41:20.370
saying, why is there only
one sister on the panel,

01:41:20.370 --> 01:41:21.624
is part of it.

01:41:21.624 --> 01:41:23.040
But the other piece
is, how are we

01:41:23.040 --> 01:41:27.950
building pipelines of leadership
and voices of sisters,

01:41:27.950 --> 01:41:31.130
especially within the movement,
where we don't immediately

01:41:31.130 --> 01:41:34.470
go to the brother who
is on TV the most,

01:41:34.470 --> 01:41:36.910
versus the sister who's
doing the better work?

01:41:36.910 --> 01:41:38.350
So I think that's part of it.

01:41:38.350 --> 01:41:41.610
Last but not least, I think that
one of the biggest challenges

01:41:41.610 --> 01:41:43.960
with our discussions around
diversity and inclusion

01:41:43.960 --> 01:41:47.170
from a corporate perspective
is even saying inclusion

01:41:47.170 --> 01:41:49.470
is the goal isn't big enough.

01:41:49.470 --> 01:41:51.700
The goal is community,
because if you

01:41:51.700 --> 01:41:54.720
have diversity and inclusion,
that just means that you're

01:41:54.720 --> 01:41:57.030
diverse enough to
check off boxes

01:41:57.030 --> 01:41:59.800
and inclusionary enough to
invite people to the table,

01:41:59.800 --> 01:42:01.900
but not deliberate
enough to make sure

01:42:01.900 --> 01:42:04.720
that those people at the table
feel like they're represented

01:42:04.720 --> 01:42:07.550
in all facets of the
DNA of the institutions

01:42:07.550 --> 01:42:08.610
that we're a part of.

01:42:08.610 --> 01:42:12.440
And only then do we
really have community.

01:42:12.440 --> 01:42:15.200
ROLAND MARTIN:
Couple of points--

01:42:15.200 --> 01:42:20.480
you don't have to
be of the same tribe

01:42:20.480 --> 01:42:23.560
to help elevate somebody else.

01:42:26.310 --> 01:42:30.170
Carmen knows this, because I've
actually told her and Linda

01:42:30.170 --> 01:42:36.930
and Tamika that I will use
my platform to elevate y'all.

01:42:36.930 --> 01:42:40.830
Not that I am against
some of the other people,

01:42:40.830 --> 01:42:43.060
but I'm in control of my stuff.

01:42:43.060 --> 01:42:44.990
And I get to pick who
I want to elevate,

01:42:44.990 --> 01:42:47.450
and I'm recognizing--
to Jeff's point-- who's

01:42:47.450 --> 01:42:48.960
actually doing the work.

01:42:48.960 --> 01:42:50.920
Some folks they're hype.

01:42:50.920 --> 01:42:52.930
Some folks actually do the work.

01:42:52.930 --> 01:42:56.420
And so that's important, because
even in corporate America

01:42:56.420 --> 01:42:58.620
you will talk to some
African-Americans, Latinos,

01:42:58.620 --> 01:43:02.160
Asians who will tell you
there was somebody white

01:43:02.160 --> 01:43:05.310
who was their best benefactor,
who supported them just

01:43:05.310 --> 01:43:05.970
because.

01:43:05.970 --> 01:43:09.727
You will find somebody black who
will say it was another sister,

01:43:09.727 --> 01:43:11.560
and it was a brother
who was being elevated.

01:43:11.560 --> 01:43:15.260
And so we look at the
individual and begin to say,

01:43:15.260 --> 01:43:17.070
you know, I'm going
to invest in you,

01:43:17.070 --> 01:43:19.040
because I think you
can do something.

01:43:19.040 --> 01:43:20.640
The last point is there here.

01:43:20.640 --> 01:43:23.830
Y'all are a part of a company--
folks in the room and also

01:43:23.830 --> 01:43:28.130
those who are watching-- that
have been revolutionaries,

01:43:28.130 --> 01:43:33.010
that have been disruptors, that
have literally changed multiple

01:43:33.010 --> 01:43:37.430
industries over the
last 10 years. .

01:43:37.430 --> 01:43:38.870
And the thing that
I think we have

01:43:38.870 --> 01:43:41.574
to think when we look at, what
can we do-- because people

01:43:41.574 --> 01:43:44.240
always say what can we do, and I
always use this example-- there

01:43:44.240 --> 01:43:48.300
literally are more people
sitting in this room

01:43:48.300 --> 01:43:51.530
right now than there
were sitting in a church

01:43:51.530 --> 01:43:57.990
basement in Montgomery in 1955.

01:43:57.990 --> 01:44:03.180
The Montgomery bus boycott we
know historically was 381 days.

01:44:03.180 --> 01:44:05.675
It was never designed
to be a 381-day boycott.

01:44:05.675 --> 01:44:09.040
It was actually a
one-day boycott.

01:44:09.040 --> 01:44:12.460
And 50,000 black folks
didn't get on the bus,

01:44:12.460 --> 01:44:18.500
and they went, hell, we
can go for two, then three.

01:44:18.500 --> 01:44:22.209
And actually, if you look at
the original list of demands,

01:44:22.209 --> 01:44:24.000
originally they didn't
even call for an end

01:44:24.000 --> 01:44:25.580
to segregated busing.

01:44:25.580 --> 01:44:28.335
They just asked for better
respect to black bus riders.

01:44:28.335 --> 01:44:30.933
Can you hire a few
more black bus drivers?

01:44:30.933 --> 01:44:34.050
Those were the initial demands.

01:44:34.050 --> 01:44:36.820
Out of Montgomery
led the lawsuit,

01:44:36.820 --> 01:44:40.770
Supreme Court ruling, then
they said, well, what else?

01:44:40.770 --> 01:44:43.470
Then they went Albany, Georgia.

01:44:43.470 --> 01:44:45.310
Then they were Selma
and Birmingham.

01:44:45.310 --> 01:44:48.350
And then they went to cities all
across the South, four college

01:44:48.350 --> 01:44:49.640
students, freshman.

01:44:49.640 --> 01:44:51.890
Didn't ask anybody's permission
at North Carolina A&amp;T,

01:44:51.890 --> 01:44:53.348
they just chose to
say, we're going

01:44:53.348 --> 01:44:55.520
to go integrate
this lunch counter.

01:44:55.520 --> 01:44:59.884
That led to it spreading like
wildfire all across the South.

01:44:59.884 --> 01:45:02.300
Imagine somebody sending a
tweet, and then all of a sudden

01:45:02.300 --> 01:45:03.750
it literally goes across.

01:45:03.750 --> 01:45:05.010
That's what that was.

01:45:05.010 --> 01:45:06.619
The point I'm
making is this here,

01:45:06.619 --> 01:45:08.285
that got us the Civil
Rights Act of '64,

01:45:08.285 --> 01:45:10.650
Voting Rights Act of '65,
Fair Housing Act of '68.

01:45:10.650 --> 01:45:12.900
That got us Arthur Fletcher
putting affirmative action

01:45:12.900 --> 01:45:16.590
in place when Nixon
became president in 1969.

01:45:16.590 --> 01:45:21.350
The point there is a handful
of people literally changed

01:45:21.350 --> 01:45:21.850
the world.

01:45:21.850 --> 01:45:26.520
If you go to Serbia,
there's an MLK drive.

01:45:26.520 --> 01:45:28.420
There's one in India.

01:45:28.420 --> 01:45:31.340
Lech Walesa, the solidarity
movement in Poland in 1980,

01:45:31.340 --> 01:45:33.580
they were singing
"We Shall Overcome."

01:45:33.580 --> 01:45:35.820
In Eastern Europe, they were
singing lift every voice

01:45:35.820 --> 01:45:37.430
and sing.

01:45:37.430 --> 01:45:40.310
The Arab Spring,
they were signs,

01:45:40.310 --> 01:45:43.250
I am a man, which are the
exact same signs black man were

01:45:43.250 --> 01:45:46.240
wearing in Memphis in 1968.

01:45:46.240 --> 01:45:52.240
So the point there is a handful
of people in a church basement

01:45:52.240 --> 01:45:55.770
literally has
impacted the world.

01:45:55.770 --> 01:45:58.240
And so you might not think
it, but if you look around

01:45:58.240 --> 01:46:02.310
in this room, you actually
have the capacity,

01:46:02.310 --> 01:46:06.230
based upon a collective
action, based upon commitment,

01:46:06.230 --> 01:46:10.390
based upon vision, based
upon being a disruptor,

01:46:10.390 --> 01:46:16.120
to change the world, just
with the people sitting

01:46:16.120 --> 01:46:17.550
in this room.

01:46:17.550 --> 01:46:20.740
To Steve's point,
what are you prepared

01:46:20.740 --> 01:46:24.830
to do when you leave this room?

01:46:24.830 --> 01:46:29.647
Dr. Steve Perry, Carmen Perez,
Jeff Johnson, Dr. Stovall.

01:46:29.647 --> 01:46:30.813
JEFF JOHNSON: Roland Martin.

01:46:30.813 --> 01:46:32.521
ROLAND MARTIN: Round
of applause, please.

01:46:32.521 --> 01:46:37.156
[APPLAUSE]

